Glad to have you here.

00:00:08.430 --> 00:00:09.180
I'm Liz Cohen.

00:00:09.180 --> 00:00:11.820
I'm dean of the Radcliffe
Institute for Advanced Study.

00:00:11.820 --> 00:00:14.760
And I'm delighted to welcome
you to today's lecture

00:00:14.760 --> 00:00:18.720
by Jacob Hacker, the Stanley
B. Resor professor of Political

00:00:18.720 --> 00:00:20.760
Science at Yale.

00:00:20.760 --> 00:00:22.350
At Radcliffe, as
many of you know,

00:00:22.350 --> 00:00:25.670
we bring together scholars,
scientists, and artists

00:00:25.670 --> 00:00:28.620
to work on the cutting
edges of their fields

00:00:28.620 --> 00:00:31.590
and across disciplinary
boundaries.

00:00:31.590 --> 00:00:33.810
And then we are
dedicated to sharing

00:00:33.810 --> 00:00:37.890
the fruits of that advance work
with broad public audiences

00:00:37.890 --> 00:00:40.710
in person and online.

00:00:40.710 --> 00:00:44.520
As an historian and dean
here at this institute,

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:46.800
I believe strongly
in our mission

00:00:46.800 --> 00:00:50.100
to bring leading scholars
and artists to Radcliffe Yard

00:00:50.100 --> 00:00:52.710
to carry out advanced work.

00:00:52.710 --> 00:00:56.940
But I have been reminded of that
mission's importance even more

00:00:56.940 --> 00:00:59.026
