in my memory,

00:01:07.410 --> 00:01:10.950
I heard and saw many
people looking for help

00:01:10.950 --> 00:01:15.840
in making sense of the campaign,
the results, and the reality

00:01:15.840 --> 00:01:18.510
of our very divided nation.

00:01:18.510 --> 00:01:23.010
Radcliffe's twin commitments to
supporting incisive scholarship

00:01:23.010 --> 00:01:26.700
on critical issues, like the
state of American politics,

00:01:26.700 --> 00:01:30.850
and then engaging the public in
serious discussion and debate,

00:01:30.850 --> 00:01:33.580
seem more urgent than ever.

00:01:33.580 --> 00:01:36.810
So I am very pleased that
Jacob Hacker and all of you

00:01:36.810 --> 00:01:39.180
are here with us today.

00:01:39.180 --> 00:01:43.680
As pundits have scrambled to
explain the victory of Donald

00:01:43.680 --> 00:01:48.060
Trump, one common analysis
has emphasized resentment

00:01:48.060 --> 00:01:50.760
on the part of Americans who
feel that the globalizing

00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:53.850
economy has left them behind.

00:01:53.850 --> 00:01:56.940
For example, the Portland
Press Herald in Maine

00:01:56.940 --> 00:02:00.420
interviewed an 80-year-old
retired mill worker

00:02:00.420 --> 00:02:03.480
who had never voted for
a Republican before,

00:02:03.480 --> 00:02:05.760
but who voted for
Trump this time,

00:02:05.760 --> 00:02:09.030
and said, in his words,
"Because Democrats used

00:02:09.030 --> 00:02:10.590
to be for the working class.

00:02:10.590 --> 00:02:12.390
I don't feel that anymore."

00:02:12.390 --> 00:02:13.740
End quote.

00:02:13.740 --> 00:02:17.700
There is good reason for many
Americans like this mill worker

00:02:17.700 --> 00:02:20.130
to believe they
are losing ground.

00:02:20.130 --> 00:02:24.150
Although the overall economy has
been thriving in recent years,

00:02:24.150 --> 00:02:26.880
and total wealth
production is up,

00:02:26.880 --> 00:02:30.600
economic inequality
has also been rising.

00:02:30.600 --> 00:02:33.690
The Economic Policy Institute,
a nonpartisan research

00:02:33.690 --> 00:02:37.560
organization, reports
that since the 1970s,

00:02:37.560 --> 00:02:43.780
real wages for the top
1% have risen 362%.

00:02:43.780 --> 00:02:47.610
Meanwhile, real wages for
most workers have stagnated.

00:02:47.610 --> 00:02:50.230
And for many, they
have actually fallen.

00:02:50.230 --> 00:02:52.710
The result is increased
wealth concentration

00:02:52.710 --> 00:02:55.920
on the very highest rungs
of the economic ladder

00:02:55.920 --> 00:02:59.820
with a shrinking share left
over for everyone else.

00:02:59.820 --> 00:03:06.330
In 2014, the wealthiest 20% of
Americans owned more than 80%

00:03:06.330 --> 00:03:08.370
of all American wealth.

00:03:08.370 --> 00:03:11.490
In contrast, the wealth
of the poorest 20%

00:03:11.490 --> 00:03:16.110
was negative, meaning that their
debts exceeded the value of all

00:03:16.110 --> 00:03:17.790
of their assets.

00:03:17.790 --> 00:03:20.640
Things have not
always been this way.

00:03:20.640 --> 00:03:23.370
In the decades
following World War II,

00:03:23.370 --> 00:03:26.160
wealth in the United
States grew and inequality

00:03:26.160 --> 00:03:28.570
shrunk at the same time.

00:03:28.570 --> 00:03:30.960
So what we are
seeing now represents

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:33.360
a fundamental change.

00:03:33.360 --> 00:03:35.610
Analysts across the
political spectrum

00:03:35.610 --> 00:03:38.130
agree that it is a
worrisome change.

00:03:38.130 --> 00:03:41.130
Even a conservative
like Alan Greenspan,

00:03:41.130 --> 00:03:42.900
former chair of the
Federal Reserve,

00:03:42.900 --> 00:03:45.130
appointed by President
Ronald Reagan,

00:03:45.130 --> 00:03:47.310
calls the current
levels of inequality,

00:03:47.310 --> 00:03:49.860
and I quote him, "not
the type of thing

00:03:49.860 --> 00:03:54.150
which a democratic society, a
capitalist, democratic society,

00:03:54.150 --> 00:03:56.770
can really accept
without addressing."

00:03:56.770 --> 00:03:58.200
End quote.

00:03:58.200 --> 00:04:00.750
Scholars of diverse
political persuasions

00:04:00.750 --> 00:04:03.120
are asking related questions.

00:04:03.120 --> 00:04:07.110
Where is the dramatic increase
in inequality coming from?

00:04:07.110 --> 00:04:10.800
Why is an economy that is
producing more wealth than ever

00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:12.990
leaving people behind?

00:04:12.990 --> 00:04:16.019
What roles have government
and private markets

00:04:16.019 --> 00:04:19.350
played in creating
economic inequality?

00:04:19.350 --> 00:04:23.100
And what can, and should,
they do to reduce it?

00:04:23.100 --> 00:04:27.630
More specifically, is government
the cause or the remedy

00:04:27.630 --> 00:04:29.640
for our present ills?

00:04:29.640 --> 00:04:32.640
Critics differ, of course,
in their explanations

00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:36.090
of how we got here
and what can be done.

00:04:36.090 --> 00:04:38.280
Jacob Hacker is a
political scientist

00:04:38.280 --> 00:04:41.010
who has dedicated
much of his career

00:04:41.010 --> 00:04:43.680
to investigating
just these questions

00:04:43.680 --> 00:04:46.440
and to seeking greater
understanding of how

00:04:46.440 --> 00:04:49.410
political and economic
leaders of different political

00:04:49.410 --> 00:04:51.690
perspectives have answered them.

00:04:51.690 --> 00:04:55.470
At the same time, he has
developed his own analyses

00:04:55.470 --> 00:04:58.800
about the causes,
consequences, and cures

00:04:58.800 --> 00:05:01.170
for the current American crisis.

00:05:01.170 --> 00:05:05.970
No subject could be more
relevant or important today.

00:05:05.970 --> 00:05:08.670
In addition to teaching
at Yale, Professor Hacker

00:05:08.670 --> 00:05:11.940
is the director of the Institute
for Social and Policy Studies

00:05:11.940 --> 00:05:15.720
there, and he is also a
frequent media commentator.

00:05:15.720 --> 00:05:19.530
Professor hacker is the author
or co-author of five books,

00:05:19.530 --> 00:05:22.800
including Winner-Take-All
Politics-- How Washington Made

00:05:22.800 --> 00:05:26.400
the Rich Richer-- And Turned
Its Back on the Middle Class,

00:05:26.400 --> 00:05:30.230
which was a New York
Times Best Seller in 2010.

00:05:30.230 --> 00:05:33.470
He co-wrote that book with
Paul Pearson, who is also

00:05:33.470 --> 00:05:37.190
the the co-author on the book
that Professor Hacker will talk

00:05:37.190 --> 00:05:41.210
to us about today, which is
entitled American Amnesia-- How

00:05:41.210 --> 00:05:44.090
the War on Government
Led Us to Forget What

00:05:44.090 --> 00:05:45.830
Made America Prosper.

00:05:45.830 --> 00:05:49.010
And if this lecture wets
your appetite for more,

00:05:49.010 --> 00:05:51.740
let me tell you that there
will be a segment on tonight's

00:05:51.740 --> 00:05:55.610
PBS NewsHour on
American amnesia,

00:05:55.610 --> 00:05:57.380
and it will also
be live-streamed

00:05:57.380 --> 00:05:59.660
if you don't catch it tonight.

00:05:59.660 --> 00:06:02.740
