00:11:00.150 --> 00:11:05.280
But this picture, American
Amnesia, a lot of people

00:11:05.280 --> 00:11:06.810
have said, well,
what a great cover.

00:11:06.810 --> 00:11:09.060
How did you get that how did
you get that Photoshopped

00:11:09.060 --> 00:11:11.850
with that wonderful fog
there around the Capitol.

00:11:11.850 --> 00:11:15.210
Well, the reality is,
it is not Photoshopped.

00:11:15.210 --> 00:11:18.400
This is the actual Capitol.

00:11:18.400 --> 00:11:22.350
And that, next to the Capitol,
is the Capitol Power Plant.

00:11:22.350 --> 00:11:24.960
It is, or was, until
it was decommissioned

00:11:24.960 --> 00:11:28.200
in 2009, the largest
single source of carbon

00:11:28.200 --> 00:11:30.270
emissions in the DC area.

00:11:30.270 --> 00:11:34.620
And it was spewing
coal ash out into one

00:11:34.620 --> 00:11:38.310
of the most disadvantaged
neighborhoods in Washington DC.

00:11:38.310 --> 00:11:43.860
Well, fortunately, it was
taken offline in 2009.

00:11:43.860 --> 00:11:47.430
Unfortunately, this issue
was raised for 30 years

00:11:47.430 --> 00:11:48.090
before that.

00:11:48.090 --> 00:11:51.760
And it was not until 2009
that it was taken down.

00:11:51.760 --> 00:11:53.910
And the reason, as
you might guess,

00:11:53.910 --> 00:11:56.400
is that the senators
from coal states

00:11:56.400 --> 00:12:01.470
were very much opposed to the
symbolic act of taking away

00:12:01.470 --> 00:12:05.630
this great monument
to American energy.

00:12:05.630 --> 00:12:11.250
And that's, in some ways, a very
nice metaphor for the argument

00:12:11.250 --> 00:12:13.930
of this book as a whole.

00:12:13.930 --> 00:12:17.820
So it's not just Washington DC.

00:12:17.820 --> 00:12:22.680
If you go back to any
city-- this is Boston, 1969.

00:12:22.680 --> 00:12:27.030
The quality of air--
not to mention air,

00:12:27.030 --> 00:12:30.600
as well as water, at the
time, was abysmal, right?

00:12:30.600 --> 00:12:35.130
So this is Boston, 1969.

00:12:35.130 --> 00:12:39.750
I have pictures of Manhattan
and Detroit and Los Angeles.

00:12:39.750 --> 00:12:42.210
These cities were deadly.

00:12:42.210 --> 00:12:46.950
The level of pollution
was such that when

00:12:46.950 --> 00:12:50.000
bad air events, as they
were sometimes called,

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:54.150
happened, literally,
hundreds of people would die,

00:12:54.150 --> 00:12:56.370
and sometimes thousands.

00:12:56.370 --> 00:13:03.660
And the fact that we don't
have such polluted air today

00:13:03.660 --> 00:13:06.210
is a reflection of
wise policy that

00:13:06.210 --> 00:13:07.590
was taken around this time.

00:13:07.590 --> 00:13:09.690
In the early 1970s,
the Clean Air Act

00:13:09.690 --> 00:13:12.600
was passed under a Republican
president, Richard Nixon.

00:13:12.600 --> 00:13:14.940
And that act, and the
subsequent amendments including,

00:13:14.940 --> 00:13:21.390
the 1991 amendments
under George H.W. Bush,

00:13:21.390 --> 00:13:25.200
dramatically improved the
quality of air in our cities.

00:13:25.200 --> 00:13:28.767
And we know that this has
made an enormous difference.

00:13:28.767 --> 00:13:30.600
And we know it from
looking at another city.

00:13:30.600 --> 00:13:36.300
This city is not
American; it's Beijing.

00:13:36.300 --> 00:13:39.990
And by comparing deaths
in rural parts of China

00:13:39.990 --> 00:13:42.810
and deaths in Beijing,
it's possible to back out

00:13:42.810 --> 00:13:46.710
rough estimates of how much life
expectancy in the United States

00:13:46.710 --> 00:13:50.130
has been improved because of
this massive improvement in air

00:13:50.130 --> 00:13:51.420
quality.

00:13:51.420 --> 00:13:54.360
And these were reported
recently in the New York Times.

00:13:54.360 --> 00:13:57.180
And I adapt that chart.

00:13:57.180 --> 00:13:59.430
And you can see that the
numbers are truly staggering.

00:13:59.430 --> 00:14:04.920
So a child born today,
as opposed to the 1970s,

00:14:04.920 --> 00:14:07.860
could expect, in one
city in West Virginia,

00:14:07.860 --> 00:14:11.000
to live for more than
five years longer

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:15.190
than his or her
counterpart in the 1970s.

00:14:15.190 --> 00:14:19.251
And the average for the United
States is around two years.

00:14:19.251 --> 00:14:21.000
But as you can see,
there are these cities

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:22.320
that are doing much better.

00:14:22.320 --> 00:14:28.170
And I'm particularly
interested in the second one

00:14:28.170 --> 00:14:31.860
down because-- as Theda Skocpol
here in the audience knows.

00:14:31.860 --> 00:14:36.780
She's been studying these
two men quite a bit lately.

00:14:36.780 --> 00:14:38.914
This is the home
of Koch industries

00:14:38.914 --> 00:14:40.830
and Charles and David
Koch who, of course, are

00:14:40.830 --> 00:14:44.070
leading critics of
active government,

00:14:44.070 --> 00:14:46.440
and in particular,
environmental laws.

00:14:46.440 --> 00:14:48.680
But apparently,
being against laws

00:14:48.680 --> 00:14:51.930
does not deprive you of
the extra years of life you

00:14:51.930 --> 00:14:54.960
get from improved air quality.

00:14:54.960 --> 00:14:59.790
And these examples tell us,
I think, two basic things.

00:14:59.790 --> 00:15:04.290
One is that government's
regulatory and spending

00:15:04.290 --> 00:15:07.740
powers, the power of government
to make people do things,

00:15:07.740 --> 00:15:12.460
can sometimes be used for
enormous positive good.

00:15:12.460 --> 00:15:14.670
And the reason is,
second, because government

00:15:14.670 --> 00:15:17.040
has distinctive capacities.

00:15:17.040 --> 00:15:19.732
Government, as I said,
has the ability--

00:15:19.732 --> 00:15:21.630
and Jane Mansbridge
has put this well--

00:15:21.630 --> 00:15:24.870
to exercise legitimate
coercion, right?

00:15:24.870 --> 00:15:27.060
Through our
democratic processes,

00:15:27.060 --> 00:15:30.570
we decide how to use
government to overcome

00:15:30.570 --> 00:15:33.000
various kinds of
collective action problems

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:38.070
and other failures of individual
decentralized behavior

00:15:38.070 --> 00:15:43.650
that would otherwise make us
poor or hurt us in other ways.

00:15:43.650 --> 00:15:46.440
I have been searching for
a way to describe this.

00:15:46.440 --> 00:15:48.750
The phrase that Paul
and I use in the book

00:15:48.750 --> 00:15:52.260
is "the mixed economy," but
that's not very evocative.

00:15:52.260 --> 00:15:55.710
So in our search,
Paul remembered

00:15:55.710 --> 00:15:58.590
that one of his advisors,
Charles Lindblom at Yale,

00:15:58.590 --> 00:16:02.280
had talked about the
mixed economy as a hand.

00:16:02.280 --> 00:16:05.650
You have the nimble fingers
of the market, right?

00:16:05.650 --> 00:16:09.907
They're very capable of
moving quickly and adjusting.

00:16:09.907 --> 00:16:11.490
And, of course, there
are four of them

00:16:11.490 --> 00:16:13.540
doing lots of different things.

00:16:13.540 --> 00:16:16.110
But the other part of your
hand that's very useful

00:16:16.110 --> 00:16:17.330
is you're thumb, right?

00:16:17.330 --> 00:16:20.100
The strong phone that
can provide the counter

00:16:20.100 --> 00:16:21.660
pressure that you need.

00:16:21.660 --> 00:16:25.717
And while you wouldn't want
to be all thumbs-- that

00:16:25.717 --> 00:16:27.300
would be pretty
awkward-- you wouldn't

00:16:27.300 --> 00:16:29.790
want to be all fingers either.

00:16:29.790 --> 00:16:33.540
It's the fact that they can
both work together, sometimes

00:16:33.540 --> 00:16:37.850
in opposition and
sometimes in cooperation,

00:16:37.850 --> 00:16:42.330
that allows us to do all the
great things that modern humans

00:16:42.330 --> 00:16:44.310
do with their opposable thumbs.

00:16:44.310 --> 00:16:47.490
And that metaphor, I
think, really sums up

00:16:47.490 --> 00:16:51.060
our view, that this is
not a zero-sum conflict

00:16:51.060 --> 00:16:52.820
between markets and
government, but rather

00:16:52.820 --> 00:16:55.890
a positive-sum bargain
that involves, of course,

00:16:55.890 --> 00:16:58.490
an enormous amount of
conflict and pressure,

00:16:58.490 --> 00:17:04.069
but also an enormous amount
of positive-sum cooperation

00:17:04.069 --> 00:17:06.810
and interplay.

00:17:06.810 --> 00:17:11.210
And what's even more important,
and what I want to emphasize,

00:17:11.210 --> 00:17:15.150
is that our nation's political
leaders once understood this.

00:17:15.150 --> 00:17:17.490
Understood this perhaps
not in the way that I've

00:17:17.490 --> 00:17:22.050
just articulated, but were
very clear that you needed

00:17:22.050 --> 00:17:27.500
an active, energetic, and yes,
sometimes coercive government

00:17:27.500 --> 00:17:28.890
to achieve prosperity.

00:17:28.890 --> 00:17:30.900
Our founders understood it.

00:17:30.900 --> 00:17:34.460
The greats of America of
economics like Adam Smith

00:17:34.460 --> 00:17:35.480
understood it.

00:17:35.480 --> 00:17:37.020
And our leaders of
the 20th century,

00:17:37.020 --> 00:17:39.770
in particular, when American
prosperity was built,

00:17:39.770 --> 00:17:41.400
definitely understood it.

00:17:41.400 --> 00:17:47.060
Today, as I'm afraid is
quite clear in the weeks

00:17:47.060 --> 00:17:50.910
since the election, many of our
leaders do not understand this.

00:17:50.910 --> 00:17:55.970
And this forgetting,
active and inadvertent,

00:17:55.970 --> 00:17:59.400
is what I want to talk
about today, this amnesia.

00:17:59.400 --> 00:18:01.470
So as I said, the
two things that I

00:18:01.470 --> 00:18:05.310
want to emphasize in discussing
the argument of the book

00:18:05.310 --> 00:18:07.680
is, first, that this
is a culmination

00:18:07.680 --> 00:18:09.200
of long-term trends.

00:18:09.200 --> 00:18:12.930
And second, and this
is equally important,

00:18:12.930 --> 00:18:15.770
that we need to have
a mixed economy.

00:18:15.770 --> 00:18:19.490
We need to have fingers and
thumbs working together, today,

00:18:19.490 --> 00:18:20.940
perhaps more than ever.

00:18:20.940 --> 00:18:25.950
And I believe we can
rebuild a mixed economy,

00:18:25.950 --> 00:18:28.720
a new kind of mixed economy,
for the 21st century.

00:18:28.720 --> 00:18:30.560
So I want to talk
about why I still

00:18:30.560 --> 00:18:35.430
have hope for that at
the end of this talk.

00:18:35.430 --> 00:18:42.620
So let's take ourselves
back in time, say,

00:18:42.620 --> 00:18:50.410
to the beginning of the
post-- to 0 AD, basically.

00:18:50.410 --> 00:18:50.910
Right?

00:18:50.910 --> 00:18:52.920
So this is a long time frame.

00:18:52.920 --> 00:18:54.420
And fortunately,
because of the work

00:18:54.420 --> 00:18:57.530
of Angus Maddison and
his collaborators,

00:18:57.530 --> 00:19:00.060
we now have a pretty good idea
of what standards of living

00:19:00.060 --> 00:19:04.940
were in some countries-- in this
case, of the United Kingdom;

00:19:04.940 --> 00:19:09.840
and starting later, the US--
for very long periods of time.

00:19:09.840 --> 00:19:11.700
And if you look at
these figures, what

00:19:11.700 --> 00:19:15.690
is really striking is that
the line was essentially flat

00:19:15.690 --> 00:19:19.010
for most of modern
human history.

00:19:19.010 --> 00:19:24.390
That jump occurs in the late
19th, early 20th century.

00:19:24.390 --> 00:19:25.850
And it's dramatic, right?

00:19:25.850 --> 00:19:32.750
The degree to which we went
from being poor, very unhealthy,

00:19:32.750 --> 00:19:36.390
as I'll show in a moment,
and very badly educated,

00:19:36.390 --> 00:19:41.510
to being rich, healthy,
and very well-educated,

00:19:41.510 --> 00:19:46.140
is almost impossible
to overstate.

00:19:46.140 --> 00:19:51.200
And this was not a natural
market development.

00:19:51.200 --> 00:19:54.510
Perhaps most important
in it was the development

00:19:54.510 --> 00:19:56.990
of the capacities and
skills of workers.

00:19:56.990 --> 00:19:59.880
And the public sector was
deeply involved in this.

00:19:59.880 --> 00:20:04.280
I'm often struck, when you hear
talk about where growth comes

00:20:04.280 --> 00:20:07.940
from, that the group that
gets most of the attention

00:20:07.940 --> 00:20:12.980
is the people at the top, the
job creators, as we're told.

00:20:12.980 --> 00:20:15.740
But if you look at why the
United States is so much more

00:20:15.740 --> 00:20:20.544
prosperous than other countries,
and why it got so much more

00:20:20.544 --> 00:20:21.960
prosperous, it's
really the degree

00:20:21.960 --> 00:20:25.410
to which mass workers
were able to become

00:20:25.410 --> 00:20:29.540
much more capable and productive
that drove this development.

00:20:29.540 --> 00:20:31.480
And that had a lot
to do with education.

00:20:31.480 --> 00:20:37.170
So it is not the case that,
as Eric Cantor put it,

00:20:37.170 --> 00:20:42.006
on Labor Day we should be
celebrating the businesses.

00:20:45.375 --> 00:20:47.750
Because of course, everyone
knows Labor Day was set aside

00:20:47.750 --> 00:20:52.570
to honor entrepreneurs.

00:20:52.570 --> 00:20:55.600
It is that we should really
be understanding the insight

00:20:55.600 --> 00:20:59.960
that Claudia Goldin and
Lawrence Katz provided us

00:20:59.960 --> 00:21:02.480
with in showing us that the
United States was really

00:21:02.480 --> 00:21:05.050
the pioneer in the
development of education.

00:21:05.050 --> 00:21:07.280
And Theda, of course,
Theda Skocpol's

00:21:07.280 --> 00:21:10.440
written very well about the
degree to which this continued.

00:21:10.440 --> 00:21:13.860
We went from being
mass universal K

00:21:13.860 --> 00:21:16.260
through 12 education,
the first country

00:21:16.260 --> 00:21:18.980
with universal high schools,
and then, of course,

00:21:18.980 --> 00:21:22.080
a world leader in college,
thanks in large part

00:21:22.080 --> 00:21:23.090
to the GI bill.

00:21:23.090 --> 00:21:25.170
And that continues
well into the 1970s

00:21:25.170 --> 00:21:29.910
with massive investments in
higher education, especially

00:21:29.910 --> 00:21:32.600
state universities.

00:21:32.600 --> 00:21:34.820
So that is one
part of this story,

00:21:34.820 --> 00:21:36.600
and it's probably the
most important part.

00:21:36.600 --> 00:21:40.200
Another part is the advancement
of science and technology,

00:21:40.200 --> 00:21:42.800
which is tied up with
this development.

00:21:42.800 --> 00:21:44.820
And as far back as
Thomas Jefferson,

00:21:44.820 --> 00:21:47.310
people understood that there
was a real market failure when

00:21:47.310 --> 00:21:51.270
it came to creating the
kind of public knowledge,

00:21:51.270 --> 00:21:57.470
like technology and
techniques like calculus,

00:21:57.470 --> 00:22:03.080
that underpin our modern
knowledge-intensive economy.

00:22:03.080 --> 00:22:05.160
And you can really
see the American role

00:22:05.160 --> 00:22:08.160
in this but looking
at Nobel prizes.

00:22:08.160 --> 00:22:11.340
So starting in the
mid-20th century,

00:22:11.340 --> 00:22:13.380
and particularly during
and after World War II,

00:22:13.380 --> 00:22:15.120
the United States came
to essentially own

00:22:15.120 --> 00:22:19.520
the field in the
Nobel Prize area.

00:22:19.520 --> 00:22:22.050
And they owned the field
because they owned the field

00:22:22.050 --> 00:22:24.180
in investment and research
and development science

00:22:24.180 --> 00:22:24.805
and technology.

00:22:24.805 --> 00:22:27.200
It didn't hurt, of course,
that lots of Europeans

00:22:27.200 --> 00:22:30.541
were also fleeing fascist
Europe and coming to the United

00:22:30.541 --> 00:22:31.040
States.

00:22:31.040 --> 00:22:34.220
But we really continued that
because of the investments

00:22:34.220 --> 00:22:36.470
we made in research
and development.

00:22:36.470 --> 00:22:39.300
And just to give you a
sense of just how huge

00:22:39.300 --> 00:22:42.470
this was, at the
end of World War II,

00:22:42.470 --> 00:22:44.780
the United States
federal government

00:22:44.780 --> 00:22:47.060
was spending more on
research and development

00:22:47.060 --> 00:22:49.490
than all businesses and
governments in the rest

00:22:49.490 --> 00:22:52.010
of the world combined.

00:22:52.010 --> 00:22:54.590
And we've, unfortunately,
fallen quite a bit,

00:22:54.590 --> 00:22:56.251
as we have in other areas.

00:22:56.251 --> 00:22:56.750
OK.

00:22:56.750 --> 00:22:58.916
So the last thing I
want to emphasize,

00:22:58.916 --> 00:23:00.290
and I've already
touched on this,

00:23:00.290 --> 00:23:04.620
is that this was not a zero-sum
story, that growth was not

00:23:04.620 --> 00:23:07.170
something where one group
was really giving up

00:23:07.170 --> 00:23:09.690
a lot to let others prosper.

00:23:09.690 --> 00:23:13.410
Of course, I'm not downplaying
the role of class conflict

00:23:13.410 --> 00:23:14.850
and redistribution
in the history

00:23:14.850 --> 00:23:17.430
of American economic
development.

00:23:17.430 --> 00:23:21.740
But if you go back
to, say, the 1920s,

00:23:21.740 --> 00:23:25.010
and look at the graduating class
of the Harvard Business School,

00:23:25.010 --> 00:23:27.930
you will see that a lot
of potential in society

00:23:27.930 --> 00:23:29.910
is not being tacked here.

00:23:29.910 --> 00:23:34.310
All the diversity
here is facial hair.

00:23:34.310 --> 00:23:39.500
And so one of the things
that both the opening up

00:23:39.500 --> 00:23:43.200
of education to
women and minorities

00:23:43.200 --> 00:23:46.140
and job opportunities
did was vastly

00:23:46.140 --> 00:23:48.470
increase the capacity
of the American society

00:23:48.470 --> 00:23:52.220
to draw on these
dispersed talents.

00:23:52.220 --> 00:23:55.770
There was a recent
study that estimated

00:23:55.770 --> 00:23:59.190
that about a fifth of total
economic growth in the United

00:23:59.190 --> 00:24:04.440
States between 1960 and 2000
was due simply to increased

00:24:04.440 --> 00:24:06.930
opportunities in the
labor market for women

00:24:06.930 --> 00:24:09.800
and minorities.

00:24:09.800 --> 00:24:12.450
So I said that this wasn't
just about income but also

00:24:12.450 --> 00:24:13.140
about health.

00:24:13.140 --> 00:24:16.010
And here, I think there's an
equally dramatic statistic

00:24:16.010 --> 00:24:16.920
we can look at.

00:24:16.920 --> 00:24:19.920
And indeed, in this case, we
could go back, but not quite as

00:24:19.920 --> 00:24:21.770
far, to the 1500s.

00:24:21.770 --> 00:24:26.500
But as you'll see, the story is
just as dramatic if we do that.

00:24:26.500 --> 00:24:30.150
So the first thing to say is
that life expectancy did not

00:24:30.150 --> 00:24:34.540
start to rise dramatically until
the 19th century, and really

00:24:34.540 --> 00:24:37.626
the late 19th and
early 20th centuries.

00:24:37.626 --> 00:24:39.500
And again, we're looking
at the United States

00:24:39.500 --> 00:24:43.620
when it sort of enters the
picture in the 19th century.

00:24:43.620 --> 00:24:48.320
But the other thing to
say is the spikes here,

00:24:48.320 --> 00:24:53.640
which are not wars, but
major diseases and plagues

00:24:53.640 --> 00:24:58.520
and famines, and the
fact is that if you look,

00:24:58.520 --> 00:25:01.650
the people who lived in,
say, British Victorian era

00:25:01.650 --> 00:25:04.410
did not have much longer life
expectancies than people who

00:25:04.410 --> 00:25:07.070
lived in, say, ancient Greece.

00:25:07.070 --> 00:25:09.390
And that's a pretty
remarkable fact.

00:25:09.390 --> 00:25:11.870
It's really the
20th century when

00:25:11.870 --> 00:25:15.560
we see these massive
increases in life expectancy

00:25:15.560 --> 00:25:17.430
and all of these other
measures of health:

00:25:17.430 --> 00:25:23.940
declining infant mortality,
increased ability in older age,

00:25:23.940 --> 00:25:24.600
and so on.

00:25:24.600 --> 00:25:28.890
And this, again, was not some
kind of natural development,

00:25:28.890 --> 00:25:31.560
as I think it's often seen.

00:25:31.560 --> 00:25:35.820
For example, the big spike
that occurs early on here

00:25:35.820 --> 00:25:38.670
is due almost entirely to
declines in infant mortality.

00:25:38.670 --> 00:25:40.924
And that, in turn, is
due almost entirely

00:25:40.924 --> 00:25:42.840
to public health efforts
that are taking place

00:25:42.840 --> 00:25:43.631
at the local level.

00:25:43.631 --> 00:25:45.300
I just read a really
fascinating article

00:25:45.300 --> 00:25:48.630
that shows not only that these
public health efforts were

00:25:48.630 --> 00:25:51.870
highly important in
improving life expectancy,

00:25:51.870 --> 00:25:56.196
but that they were driven by the
mobilization of women's groups

00:25:56.196 --> 00:25:58.320
in these areas, a kind of
continuation of the story

00:25:58.320 --> 00:26:01.260
that Theda Skocpol tells in
her book Protecting Soldiers

00:26:01.260 --> 00:26:03.420
and Mothers, about
mothers pensions.

00:26:03.420 --> 00:26:05.510
So there was a political
story behind this.

00:26:05.510 --> 00:26:09.300
It was a story of enlarged
participation by women.

00:26:09.300 --> 00:26:11.750
It was a story of
greater responsiveness

00:26:11.750 --> 00:26:16.934
of local and state and national
elites to ordinary citizens.

00:26:16.934 --> 00:26:19.350
But it resulted-- in there
was, of course, the development

00:26:19.350 --> 00:26:21.270
of science, the germ
theory of disease,

00:26:21.270 --> 00:26:24.260
which postdates the early
public health efforts, but is

00:26:24.260 --> 00:26:27.540
at the heart of a lot of
the later work that's done.

00:26:27.540 --> 00:26:29.670
And so this goes
to the expansion

00:26:29.670 --> 00:26:32.160
of insurance and
medical technology

00:26:32.160 --> 00:26:34.890
and clinical practice, right?

00:26:34.890 --> 00:26:40.680
The great divide that we cross
in the early 20th century

00:26:40.680 --> 00:26:42.550
is not just one of
income and health.

00:26:42.550 --> 00:26:47.990
It's also a shift
from being worse off

00:26:47.990 --> 00:26:50.270
if we saw a doctor
to being better off.

00:26:50.270 --> 00:26:53.250
So there's a great
quote from one

00:26:53.250 --> 00:26:55.440
of the presidents
of Harvard, where

00:26:55.440 --> 00:26:58.730
he says a random patient
seeing a random doctor

00:26:58.730 --> 00:27:02.400
for random condition did
not, until this period,

00:27:02.400 --> 00:27:07.560
have more than a 50/50 chance of
benefiting from the encounter.

00:27:07.560 --> 00:27:10.560
Now, it's not 100% today,
but it's a lot better.

00:27:10.560 --> 00:27:11.940
And this wasn't the only thing.

00:27:11.940 --> 00:27:13.170
It wasn't just medical care.

00:27:13.170 --> 00:27:14.510
It wasn't just insurance.

00:27:14.510 --> 00:27:18.020
It was also an
enormous expansion

00:27:18.020 --> 00:27:21.570
of things that are protecting
people against themselves.

00:27:21.570 --> 00:27:24.170
And this, I know, is a
hard subject to take up.

00:27:24.170 --> 00:27:28.010
It reeks a little
bit of paternalism.

00:27:28.010 --> 00:27:37.230
But the fact is that the decline
in smoking and the improvement

00:27:37.230 --> 00:27:39.740
in auto safety, which often
involves requiring people

00:27:39.740 --> 00:27:42.330
to have safety measures,
was also enormously

00:27:42.330 --> 00:27:46.460
important in this story.

00:27:46.460 --> 00:27:50.981
So this is the smoking picture.

00:27:50.981 --> 00:27:51.480
Right?

00:27:51.480 --> 00:27:54.360
So the Surgeon General's report
and the anti-smoking efforts

00:27:54.360 --> 00:27:56.910
of this period make an
enormous difference.

00:27:56.910 --> 00:28:03.030
Just recently, there
was some controversy

00:28:03.030 --> 00:28:07.110
over that concussion
scandals within the NFL.

00:28:07.110 --> 00:28:10.735
And the New York Times
revealed that the NFL

00:28:10.735 --> 00:28:12.360
had been using some
of the same lawyers

00:28:12.360 --> 00:28:14.940
that the tobacco
industry used, which

00:28:14.940 --> 00:28:18.910
led to the following
quote from the NFL.

00:28:18.910 --> 00:28:23.070
My colleague, Paul Pearson, says
when the NFL says you're bad,

00:28:23.070 --> 00:28:23.966
you're really bad.

00:28:23.966 --> 00:28:24.466
OK.

00:28:24.466 --> 00:28:25.680
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:25.680 --> 00:28:27.680
And this is the same
story with lead,

00:28:27.680 --> 00:28:31.560
which the decline of lead
in our-- the decline of lead

00:28:31.560 --> 00:28:34.490
in our cities, which
improves cognitive function,

00:28:34.490 --> 00:28:37.700
is probably implicated
in the decline in crime.

00:28:37.700 --> 00:28:40.790
When we talk about
Flint, we say oh my god.

00:28:40.790 --> 00:28:43.460
And it is just a
horrible regression.

00:28:43.460 --> 00:28:48.570
But the fact is
that in the 1970s,

00:28:48.570 --> 00:28:51.510
large portions of preschool
kids had lead levels

00:28:51.510 --> 00:28:54.770
much higher than those
that we see in Flint.

00:28:54.770 --> 00:28:56.910
For example, a lot
of people think

00:28:56.910 --> 00:29:00.690
that 5 micrograms per deciliter
is kind of the upper limit

00:29:00.690 --> 00:29:04.680
that you should be exposed to.

00:29:04.680 --> 00:29:07.020
And as you can see, in
the mid-'70s, your average

00:29:07.020 --> 00:29:11.291
preschool kid was exposed to
something like five times that.

00:29:11.291 --> 00:29:11.790
OK.

00:29:11.790 --> 00:29:17.760
So this is the
story of how we got

00:29:17.760 --> 00:29:19.520
so much richer and healthier.

00:29:19.520 --> 00:29:22.620
So what is the story of
how this came undone?

00:29:22.620 --> 00:29:24.290
Because it has come undone.

00:29:24.290 --> 00:29:27.180
In area after area that we
write about in the book,

00:29:27.180 --> 00:29:30.200
we are no longer
leading the pack.

00:29:30.200 --> 00:29:34.690
The example that I
find, in some ways--

00:29:34.690 --> 00:29:37.320
and I'm just going to skip over
this-- but the example that I

00:29:37.320 --> 00:29:39.680
find, in some ways,
most revealing

00:29:39.680 --> 00:29:42.180
is that Americans used to be
the tallest people in the world

00:29:42.180 --> 00:29:43.980
by a very large margin.

00:29:43.980 --> 00:29:47.240
We were much taller at the
time of the revolution.

00:29:47.240 --> 00:29:50.910
We were taller
than the Europeans

00:29:50.910 --> 00:29:52.984
at the time of World War II.

00:29:52.984 --> 00:29:54.900
But we're not the tallest
people in the world,

00:29:54.900 --> 00:29:56.670
and this is true
even if you look

00:29:56.670 --> 00:30:00.690
at people who are
native-born white Americans.

00:30:00.690 --> 00:30:03.570
So this is the US trend,
and these are basically

00:30:03.570 --> 00:30:05.470
cohorts when you're born.

00:30:05.470 --> 00:30:06.930
Here is the Netherlands.

00:30:06.930 --> 00:30:08.820
My wife's family is
from the Netherlands.

00:30:08.820 --> 00:30:12.020
Whenever I go over there, I
realized just how short I am.

00:30:12.020 --> 00:30:15.290
And you can see, well, there's
your average Dutch build

00:30:15.290 --> 00:30:18.870
and your average American build,
and there is a difference.

00:30:18.870 --> 00:30:22.520
Germans have done a
little better-- a little

00:30:22.520 --> 00:30:23.790
less well than the Dutch.

00:30:23.790 --> 00:30:25.620
But in general,
basically, we have

00:30:25.620 --> 00:30:28.890
ceased to be this kind
of towering people

00:30:28.890 --> 00:30:31.700
at the same time as we've fallen
behind on these other measures.

00:30:31.700 --> 00:30:32.200
OK.

00:30:32.200 --> 00:30:37.860
So I very briefly want to say a
bit about what underscored this

00:30:37.860 --> 00:30:39.560
and how it fell apart.

00:30:39.560 --> 00:30:42.570
And the crucial point
that I want to make

00:30:42.570 --> 00:30:45.960
is that there was a political
and economic coalition

00:30:45.960 --> 00:30:48.750
of business leaders and
moderate Republicans that

00:30:48.750 --> 00:30:51.450
was at the heart of the
success of the mixed economy.

00:30:51.450 --> 00:30:54.930
In some ways, you can tell the
story of the transformation

00:30:54.930 --> 00:30:58.470
from one Romney to another.

00:30:58.470 --> 00:31:01.050
From George Romney, the
Governor of Michigan,

00:31:01.050 --> 00:31:04.940
who was an auto
manufacturer, to Mitt Romney,

00:31:04.940 --> 00:31:08.910
the-- we all know
who Mitt Romney is.

00:31:08.910 --> 00:31:10.470
I can move more
quickly than that.

00:31:10.470 --> 00:31:14.400
So what is the nature
of this transformation?

00:31:14.400 --> 00:31:16.680
After all, they're both
Republicans in blue states.

00:31:16.680 --> 00:31:20.430
They're both relatively moderate
within their own parties.

00:31:20.430 --> 00:31:23.630
And they both have a private
sector business experience.

00:31:23.630 --> 00:31:26.730
Well, one of the most
fundamental differences

00:31:26.730 --> 00:31:30.270
is that George Romney comes
from the manufacturing world.

00:31:30.270 --> 00:31:33.120
And he himself is
very clear that there

00:31:33.120 --> 00:31:35.820
needs to be a great deal of
equity within the workplace.

00:31:35.820 --> 00:31:37.830
And he's supportive of unions.

00:31:37.830 --> 00:31:41.160
At the same time,
George Romney is opposed

00:31:41.160 --> 00:31:42.780
to the Goldwater conservatism.

00:31:42.780 --> 00:31:46.380
And at the time-- so if
you think of Mitt Romney,

00:31:46.380 --> 00:31:49.710
he's coming out of
the finance world,

00:31:49.710 --> 00:31:52.050
the world of Bain
Capital, which is

00:31:52.050 --> 00:31:55.230
much more about slicing
and dicing companies

00:31:55.230 --> 00:31:57.690
and about shorter-term
economic gains.

00:31:57.690 --> 00:32:01.980
So if you think about these two
figures as business leaders,

00:32:01.980 --> 00:32:04.560
as we discussed in the
book, the transformation

00:32:04.560 --> 00:32:07.560
of the business community,
both the organizations that

00:32:07.560 --> 00:32:12.180
represent it and business
leaders' own orientation

00:32:12.180 --> 00:32:13.680
toward the mixed
economy are really

00:32:13.680 --> 00:32:16.800
transformed over this
period by financialization

00:32:16.800 --> 00:32:20.800
and by changes in organized
business leadership.

00:32:20.800 --> 00:32:23.250
So this man, Tom
Donohue, is the head

00:32:23.250 --> 00:32:24.690
of the Chamber of Commerce.

00:32:24.690 --> 00:32:26.940
The Chamber of Commerce,
under his leadership,

00:32:26.940 --> 00:32:29.760
has gone from being kind of
a staid, moderate business

00:32:29.760 --> 00:32:32.880
organization to being closely
allied with Republicans

00:32:32.880 --> 00:32:35.800
and much more of a lobbying shop
for parochial private sector

00:32:35.800 --> 00:32:36.300
interest.

00:32:36.300 --> 00:32:41.480
This, after all, is what the
sign on Tom Donohue's desk

00:32:41.480 --> 00:32:43.350
reads, "Show me the money."

00:32:43.350 --> 00:32:47.070
And as Theda Skocpol has
very carefully shown,

00:32:47.070 --> 00:32:48.810
the other major
business group that

00:32:48.810 --> 00:32:51.840
has become much more
powerful, besides the Chamber

00:32:51.840 --> 00:32:53.490
of Commerce, is
the Koch network.

00:32:53.490 --> 00:32:56.410
And the Koch network
is, of course,

00:32:56.410 --> 00:33:00.420
is not so much
parochial in this way.

00:33:00.420 --> 00:33:02.770
But it's very extreme,
ideologically.

00:33:02.770 --> 00:33:05.130
And it's probably
roughly equal in size

00:33:05.130 --> 00:33:06.930
or even larger to the
Chamber of Commerce.

00:33:06.930 --> 00:33:09.750
Now, one feature
of this development

00:33:09.750 --> 00:33:12.510
that I want to emphasize is that
it takes us back, in a sense,

00:33:12.510 --> 00:33:15.100
to an older, more
feudal economy.

00:33:15.100 --> 00:33:17.130
And this is the Rhine River.

00:33:17.130 --> 00:33:18.930
These are the
castles on the Rhine

00:33:18.930 --> 00:33:21.630
that the robber barons,
as they were called,

00:33:21.630 --> 00:33:26.310
used to basically block
commerce and take tolls,

00:33:26.310 --> 00:33:31.255
thus shutting down European
trade in the 1500s.

00:33:31.255 --> 00:33:36.150
And in many ways, today's
business associations

00:33:36.150 --> 00:33:39.480
and top corporate leaders are
much more operating in a world

00:33:39.480 --> 00:33:43.590
where they're able to use
market power and political power

00:33:43.590 --> 00:33:44.950
to skim off the top.

00:33:44.950 --> 00:33:49.455
As Liz was talking about
before, the rise in inequality

00:33:49.455 --> 00:33:52.080
is driven, in substantial part,
by what's happening at the top.

00:33:52.080 --> 00:33:53.610
And there's more
and more evidence

00:33:53.610 --> 00:33:57.330
that this is about, in
many cases, rent-seeking.

00:33:57.330 --> 00:34:00.120
That is, above market
returns that are

00:34:00.120 --> 00:34:01.510
a result of political power.

00:34:01.510 --> 00:34:03.750
So for example, in
our health care sector

00:34:03.750 --> 00:34:08.409
where we spend vastly
more than other countries,

00:34:08.409 --> 00:34:11.969
we're spending much more
for mediocre results.

00:34:11.969 --> 00:34:16.679
There's enormous evidence
that the lobbying activities

00:34:16.679 --> 00:34:21.659
and market power of private
actors from providers

00:34:21.659 --> 00:34:24.330
to pharmaceutical
manufacturers is

00:34:24.330 --> 00:34:26.870
at the heart of the
degree to which we--

00:34:26.870 --> 00:34:28.679
that our costs are so high.

00:34:28.679 --> 00:34:31.409
And those costs, of course, are
enormous reason for the squeeze

00:34:31.409 --> 00:34:33.659
on other parts of our budget.

00:34:33.659 --> 00:34:36.270
The other big change
that is reflected

00:34:36.270 --> 00:34:41.760
in this transformation
is a transformation

00:34:41.760 --> 00:34:43.860
of the ideology of
the Republican Party.

00:34:43.860 --> 00:34:46.284
So if the business world has
become more financialized

00:34:46.284 --> 00:34:47.659
and has organized
representatives

00:34:47.659 --> 00:34:51.929
to become either more
mercenary or more extreme,

00:34:51.929 --> 00:34:54.247
the Republican Party has
become much more conservative.

00:34:54.247 --> 00:34:55.830
And I don't think
this is particularly

00:34:55.830 --> 00:34:57.690
controversial at this point.

00:34:57.690 --> 00:35:01.570
But I just want to make clear
that part of this conservatism,

00:35:01.570 --> 00:35:05.340
it goes hand-in-hand
with some solicitousness

00:35:05.340 --> 00:35:06.930
towards these
corporate interests.

00:35:06.930 --> 00:35:09.450
But it's also an
anti-government ideology

00:35:09.450 --> 00:35:12.690
that is quite explicit
about seeing government

00:35:12.690 --> 00:35:15.450
as the problem, as
Ronald Reagan put it.

00:35:15.450 --> 00:35:18.720
And more than that, the
strategies of this movement

00:35:18.720 --> 00:35:21.300
have been much more
focused around obstruction

00:35:21.300 --> 00:35:23.500
and making it difficult
for government to act.

00:35:23.500 --> 00:35:27.250
So in a lot of
ways, the strategies

00:35:27.250 --> 00:35:30.930
of, first, Newt Gingrich
and Mitch McConnell

00:35:30.930 --> 00:35:34.200
have basically been fomenting
anti-government sentiment,

00:35:34.200 --> 00:35:36.652
in part by making it
very difficult to govern.

00:35:36.652 --> 00:35:37.860
You see this again and again.

00:35:37.860 --> 00:35:40.230
And what is particularly
important to understand here

00:35:40.230 --> 00:35:43.950
is that the mixed economy
rested heavily on the ability

00:35:43.950 --> 00:35:46.640
to form moderate
bipartisan compromises.

00:35:46.640 --> 00:35:50.940
And as late as the early 1990s,
you still saw those forming.

00:35:50.940 --> 00:35:55.050
But this twin move of
the Republican Party

00:35:55.050 --> 00:35:58.680
toward both a more conservative
ideology and a more

00:35:58.680 --> 00:36:00.990
obstructionist stance
has made it much harder

00:36:00.990 --> 00:36:03.130
to use government
in a positive way.

00:36:03.130 --> 00:36:07.530
Now, in my conclusion, I want
to talk just a little bit

00:36:07.530 --> 00:36:10.140
about the current leadership.

00:36:10.140 --> 00:36:12.870
And I just want to say let
the record show that I've

00:36:12.870 --> 00:36:16.080
spoken for about 50 minutes
and have really not mentioned

00:36:16.080 --> 00:36:16.980
Donald Trump yet.

00:36:16.980 --> 00:36:20.010
So that's quite an
achievement, I think.

00:36:20.010 --> 00:36:22.410
And in fact, I want to talk
not about Donald Trump first.

00:36:22.410 --> 00:36:25.080
I want to mention Paul Ryan.

00:36:25.080 --> 00:36:33.210
So Paul Ryan is--
if you look at this,

00:36:33.210 --> 00:36:34.680
these are from
D-NOMINATE scores,

00:36:34.680 --> 00:36:36.450
so ignore this dimension.

00:36:36.450 --> 00:36:37.570
Just think about this.

00:36:37.570 --> 00:36:41.910
This is a dimension that goes
towards more conservatism.

00:36:41.910 --> 00:36:44.340
Ryan is quite a bit more
conservative than Boehner.

00:36:44.340 --> 00:36:46.740
Boehner, by the way, was on
the right edge of his party

00:36:46.740 --> 00:36:48.460
when he came into Congress.

00:36:48.460 --> 00:36:51.740
And, of course, he
then became, first,

00:36:51.740 --> 00:36:53.580
a the kind of centrist
within his own party,

00:36:53.580 --> 00:36:55.890
and then actually
fairly moderate

00:36:55.890 --> 00:36:58.480
relative to these Freedom
Caucus members, who

00:36:58.480 --> 00:37:00.150
are the most conservative wing.

00:37:00.150 --> 00:37:03.160
Ryan is much more
comfortably within that.

00:37:03.160 --> 00:37:07.650
And put aside his
expressed enthusiasm

00:37:07.650 --> 00:37:10.260
for the writings of Ayn Rand.

00:37:10.260 --> 00:37:12.900
If you look at the Ryan
budgets that have come out year

00:37:12.900 --> 00:37:15.570
after year, they have involved
three central elements,

00:37:15.570 --> 00:37:19.440
massive tax cuts that are not
really funded in the future

00:37:19.440 --> 00:37:23.370
and thus will devastate
the federal budget,

00:37:23.370 --> 00:37:25.920
disproportionate--
where the cuts are made,

00:37:25.920 --> 00:37:30.660
disproportionate cuts for
the poor, and finally,

00:37:30.660 --> 00:37:33.990
dismantling of key core parts
of the social insurance state,

00:37:33.990 --> 00:37:37.770
notably the movement of Medicare
away from a guaranteed benefit

00:37:37.770 --> 00:37:41.820
towards a voucher that it
will, over time, erode relative

00:37:41.820 --> 00:37:43.360
to the cost of medical care.

00:37:43.360 --> 00:37:46.920
There is no sign that Paul
Ryan has changed his view

00:37:46.920 --> 00:37:48.220
on these fundamental issues.

00:37:48.220 --> 00:37:50.070
In fact, before the
election, in a moment

00:37:50.070 --> 00:37:52.167
that was kind of missed
by many commentators,

00:37:52.167 --> 00:37:54.750
Paul Ryan got up there and said
here's what we're going to do.

00:37:54.750 --> 00:37:55.770
We're going to
pass all this stuff

00:37:55.770 --> 00:37:57.228
through the
reconciliation process.

00:37:57.228 --> 00:37:59.071
If we have a
Republican president,

00:37:59.071 --> 00:38:00.570
that's the budget
process that can't

00:38:00.570 --> 00:38:02.130
be subject to a filibuster.

00:38:02.130 --> 00:38:05.130
If we had a Republican
president, he'll sign it.

00:38:05.130 --> 00:38:08.670
Well, now they do, and I
think he will-- certainly,

00:38:08.670 --> 00:38:12.342
on many of the proposals that
fall short of the restructuring

00:38:12.342 --> 00:38:14.800
of Medicare, which is where I
think there would be the most

00:38:14.800 --> 00:38:17.010
pushback.

00:38:17.010 --> 00:38:18.870
But the other
thing I want to say

00:38:18.870 --> 00:38:21.330
about the continuation
of these trends

00:38:21.330 --> 00:38:23.550
with the contemporary
Republican Congress

00:38:23.550 --> 00:38:26.250
is that the other key
figure is Mitch McConnell.

00:38:26.250 --> 00:38:29.070
Mitch McConnell, in my view,
and as we argue in the book,

00:38:29.070 --> 00:38:31.740
has sort of cracked the
code of American politics.

00:38:31.740 --> 00:38:34.080
He realized that in
our political system,

00:38:34.080 --> 00:38:38.040
it was possible
to foment distrust

00:38:38.040 --> 00:38:39.630
in American political
institutions.

00:38:39.630 --> 00:38:41.790
And the levels of
distrust that we see today

00:38:41.790 --> 00:38:42.930
are truly remarkable.

00:38:42.930 --> 00:38:43.440
Right?

00:38:43.440 --> 00:38:45.930
We've never seen
public trust so low.

00:38:45.930 --> 00:38:48.480
And I really think we
should not go too deeply

00:38:48.480 --> 00:38:51.090
in trying to understand
some of the core elements

00:38:51.090 --> 00:38:52.860
of this election.

00:38:52.860 --> 00:38:55.470
There was dissatisfaction
with many aspects

00:38:55.470 --> 00:38:57.090
of where our country is going.

00:38:57.090 --> 00:39:00.986
The party in power had been in
power already for eight years.

00:39:00.986 --> 00:39:02.610
And people don't
believe in government.

00:39:02.610 --> 00:39:04.235
They've been pressing
the "mad as hell"

00:39:04.235 --> 00:39:07.476
button every few elections,
and things have not

00:39:07.476 --> 00:39:09.600
been getting better, and
they're mad as hell again.

00:39:09.600 --> 00:39:12.880
Now, the coalition behind
that was different.

00:39:12.880 --> 00:39:14.646
And the response,
unfortunately, I think,

00:39:14.646 --> 00:39:16.020
will be quite
different than what

00:39:16.020 --> 00:39:19.980
many of those pressing the
"mad as hell" button want.

00:39:19.980 --> 00:39:23.290
But I think it's very much a
continuation of these trends.

00:39:23.290 --> 00:39:27.360
So in my last
remarks, I just want

00:39:27.360 --> 00:39:32.190
to say a little bit about why
I think we should, nonetheless,

00:39:32.190 --> 00:39:34.800
believe that there is
prospect for a mixed

00:39:34.800 --> 00:39:36.980
economy for the 21st century.

00:39:36.980 --> 00:39:41.190
And at the end of the book,
Paul and I say there's good news

00:39:41.190 --> 00:39:42.065
and there's bad news.

00:39:42.065 --> 00:39:44.231
And since I've been talking
about a lot of bad news,

00:39:44.231 --> 00:39:45.640
I'll start with the good news.

00:39:45.640 --> 00:39:48.630
And the good news is that there
is a lot of money on the table.

00:39:48.630 --> 00:39:53.070
There are a lot of positive-sum
bargains we're not making.

00:39:53.070 --> 00:39:55.620
Perhaps, we will
seize on some of them.

00:39:55.620 --> 00:39:58.860
I am very doubtful about the
Trump infrastructure proposals.

00:39:58.860 --> 00:40:00.480
But that's certainly
an area in which

00:40:00.480 --> 00:40:02.490
we've massively
been underperforming

00:40:02.490 --> 00:40:04.040
because of lack of investment.

00:40:04.040 --> 00:40:06.375
So, unfortunately--
I say unfortunately

00:40:06.375 --> 00:40:08.250
because I think that
the Trump infrastructure

00:40:08.250 --> 00:40:10.320
proposals, as they've
shaped up, look

00:40:10.320 --> 00:40:13.230
very much like privatization
of public assets

00:40:13.230 --> 00:40:16.810
with little positive
long-term benefit.

00:40:16.810 --> 00:40:20.640
But the truth is that there
are many areas in health,

00:40:20.640 --> 00:40:24.270
in economic inequality
and security,

00:40:24.270 --> 00:40:27.040
in infrastructure and research
and development, where

00:40:27.040 --> 00:40:29.560
we have not been making the
investments that we should.

00:40:29.560 --> 00:40:34.680
And if we did, we would witness
significant economic growth,

00:40:34.680 --> 00:40:37.770
and it would be broadly shared.

00:40:37.770 --> 00:40:39.079
So that's the good news.

00:40:39.079 --> 00:40:40.870
And I also think another
piece of good news

00:40:40.870 --> 00:40:42.790
is that I think it's
completely compatible

00:40:42.790 --> 00:40:46.560
with our broad
political institutions

00:40:46.560 --> 00:40:48.810
to achieve that goal.

00:40:48.810 --> 00:40:52.230
But the bad news is that
it's going to be hard.

00:40:52.230 --> 00:40:54.970
And that's what--
it's not something

00:40:54.970 --> 00:40:56.200
that people want to hear.

00:40:56.200 --> 00:40:58.230
There is no magic bullet.

00:40:58.230 --> 00:41:00.460
We're not going to reverse
these trends simply

00:41:00.460 --> 00:41:04.955
by reducing lobbying or
eliminating Citizens United.

00:41:04.955 --> 00:41:06.580
We're going to have
to do three things.

00:41:06.580 --> 00:41:10.210
And they're as difficult as
they are easy to articulate.

00:41:10.210 --> 00:41:13.600
First, we have to get government
moving again and working.

00:41:13.600 --> 00:41:16.750
If it doesn't work,
then this doom cycle,

00:41:16.750 --> 00:41:19.650
this doom loop of dysfunction
we've been seeing, continues.

00:41:19.650 --> 00:41:23.350
Second, we have to
increase mass pressure

00:41:23.350 --> 00:41:24.820
on elite organizations.

00:41:24.820 --> 00:41:28.240
And labor unions are facing
a mass extinction event.

00:41:28.240 --> 00:41:30.480
Where will that
pressure come from?

00:41:30.480 --> 00:41:33.250
We need to think about that,
and we need to be part of that.

00:41:33.250 --> 00:41:38.620
And finally, we have to
encourage cross pressure

00:41:38.620 --> 00:41:39.520
among elites.

00:41:39.520 --> 00:41:44.640
We need Silicon Valley
standing up and speaking out

00:41:44.640 --> 00:41:48.520
for the degree to which the
political economy that we need

00:41:48.520 --> 00:41:50.394
to create for the
21st century for it

00:41:50.394 --> 00:41:51.810
to be a thriving
knowledge economy

00:41:51.810 --> 00:41:55.890
is threatened by
these developments.

00:41:55.890 --> 00:41:57.776
It's a huge issue,
and it was really

00:41:57.776 --> 00:41:58.900
in this election we saw it.

00:41:58.900 --> 00:42:02.740
Prosperity is increasingly
concentrated in urban knowledge

00:42:02.740 --> 00:42:05.080
centers where these
agglomeration effects created

00:42:05.080 --> 00:42:07.660
by technology are greatest.

00:42:07.660 --> 00:42:10.890
And that prosperity has
not been shared broadly.

00:42:10.890 --> 00:42:13.270
It is the future of our
economy, but it's a future

00:42:13.270 --> 00:42:15.660
that all Americans
need to be part of.

00:42:15.660 --> 00:42:19.330
So we have the
grounds for growth,

00:42:19.330 --> 00:42:21.960
and we know what the
basic formula is.

00:42:21.960 --> 00:42:24.280
And I actually think that
given what I've just said,

00:42:24.280 --> 00:42:27.520
there's a very large prospect
that the current political

00:42:27.520 --> 00:42:30.580
regime will overreach
and create opportunities

00:42:30.580 --> 00:42:33.000
for that kind of building
of a long-term movement

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:34.440
for effective governance.

00:42:34.440 --> 00:42:36.660
But it's not going to
happen unless we recognize

00:42:36.660 --> 00:42:40.810
how deep the problem is and
how fundamental the role

00:42:40.810 --> 00:42:44.080
of government is in
creating our prosperity.

00:42:44.080 --> 00:42:47.040
Or as Paul Pierson and I put
it at the end of our book quite

00:42:47.040 --> 00:42:50.200
succinctly, "The government
that governs best

00:42:50.200 --> 00:42:52.140
has to govern quite a bit."

00:42:52.140 --> 00:42:53.250
Thank you.

00:42:53.250 --> 00:42:56.428
