00:45:46.720 --> 00:45:50.080
how much slower you
are when you give

00:45:50.080 --> 00:45:53.440
a talk than you were in your
mind when you were writing it.

00:45:53.440 --> 00:45:55.420
So I actually did have
to omit a little bit

00:45:55.420 --> 00:45:59.950
of a discussion of this
really important dimension.

00:45:59.950 --> 00:46:03.280
Though, I also think it's
fair to say looking back

00:46:03.280 --> 00:46:05.780
at the book, and I
recognized it at the time

00:46:05.780 --> 00:46:08.336
we were finishing it up, that
it says much less about race

00:46:08.336 --> 00:46:08.960
than it should.

00:46:08.960 --> 00:46:13.300
So let me say a little bit
about how I think that fits in.

00:46:13.300 --> 00:46:16.690
So, first of all, one cannot
deny the degree to which

00:46:16.690 --> 00:46:21.550
American politics has shifted
to onto a racial axis.

00:46:21.550 --> 00:46:25.510
Or returned might be the
better way to put it.

00:46:25.510 --> 00:46:31.100
And there is a lot of
writing in discussing

00:46:31.100 --> 00:46:34.390
this election about class
and differences of class.

00:46:34.390 --> 00:46:38.350
And I think that there is some
evidence of a certain kind

00:46:38.350 --> 00:46:39.880
of class differences.

00:46:39.880 --> 00:46:43.120
Whites without a college
degree, definitely,

00:46:43.120 --> 00:46:45.550
were much more strongly
Republican in this election

00:46:45.550 --> 00:46:48.190
than they have been
in recent elections.

00:46:48.190 --> 00:46:51.040
But that was a difference
in degree, not kind.

00:46:51.040 --> 00:46:52.780
I think what was
really striking to me

00:46:52.780 --> 00:46:56.170
was the degree to which
this election became

00:46:56.170 --> 00:46:59.680
much more explicitly
racialized than any one I've

00:46:59.680 --> 00:47:01.570
seen in my lifetime.

00:47:01.570 --> 00:47:04.750
And the patterns of voting,
of course, reflected that.

00:47:04.750 --> 00:47:06.280
People, right
after the election,

00:47:06.280 --> 00:47:08.440
were talking about
how Clinton just

00:47:08.440 --> 00:47:10.210
didn't bring out
African-Americans

00:47:10.210 --> 00:47:11.260
and Hispanics.

00:47:11.260 --> 00:47:14.170
As I'm looking at these
numbers-- and the turnout

00:47:14.170 --> 00:47:14.830
is one issue.

00:47:14.830 --> 00:47:17.389
But in terms of the
rates of support,

00:47:17.389 --> 00:47:19.430
especially among Hispanics,
it's just remarkable.

00:47:19.430 --> 00:47:22.480
It's quite clear they understood
what Donald Trump was saying

00:47:22.480 --> 00:47:26.290
and the threat that he posed
to people with brown skin.

00:47:26.290 --> 00:47:29.710
So the way in which it fits
into our larger story, I think,

00:47:29.710 --> 00:47:31.280
is twofold.

00:47:31.280 --> 00:47:36.010
One, we talk about, and another
we should have talked about.

00:47:36.010 --> 00:47:38.830
So one we talk about
is the way in which--

00:47:38.830 --> 00:47:43.060
this idea of the state as this
agent of redistribution, which

00:47:43.060 --> 00:47:45.460
I think is very common
among both Liberals

00:47:45.460 --> 00:47:46.710
and Conservatives.

00:47:46.710 --> 00:47:49.690
It really misses the way in
which the government policies

00:47:49.690 --> 00:47:51.610
create these kind of
positive-sum bargains.

00:47:51.610 --> 00:47:56.230
The degree to which bringing
African-Americans fully

00:47:56.230 --> 00:48:00.840
into our economy was
vastly wealth-producing

00:48:00.840 --> 00:48:02.780
for the economy as a
whole, and of course,

00:48:02.780 --> 00:48:08.380
for those who were able to,
for the first time, become

00:48:08.380 --> 00:48:12.250
a part of the American dream.

00:48:12.250 --> 00:48:14.770
And at a time, of course,
where that dream was just

00:48:14.770 --> 00:48:17.100
about to hit the rocks.

00:48:17.100 --> 00:48:21.820
But the language of
redistribution on the right

00:48:21.820 --> 00:48:23.800
is the language of
makers and takers.

00:48:23.800 --> 00:48:27.820
And there's no question
that image, as lots of work

00:48:27.820 --> 00:48:30.760
has shown, is a
highly-racialized image.

00:48:30.760 --> 00:48:33.130
So there's a reason that
Medicare and Social Security,

00:48:33.130 --> 00:48:35.050
which are seen as
predominantly helping

00:48:35.050 --> 00:48:37.540
upstanding, hardworking,
white Americans

00:48:37.540 --> 00:48:45.160
are not viewed as part of this
miasma of welfare dependency.

00:48:45.160 --> 00:48:46.930
And there's a reason
there's a reason

00:48:46.930 --> 00:48:52.990
as well that Donald
Trump and his supporters

00:48:52.990 --> 00:48:55.390
saw the campaign
around-- oriented

00:48:55.390 --> 00:48:58.027
the campaign around
immigration and the changing

00:48:58.027 --> 00:48:59.110
complexion of the country.

00:48:59.110 --> 00:49:02.620
And I think that we just cannot
understand that being the way

00:49:02.620 --> 00:49:05.590
in which distrust of government
has risen in the United States

00:49:05.590 --> 00:49:07.960
without understanding that
it partly represents a very

00:49:07.960 --> 00:49:11.380
fundamental backlash against
the changing demography

00:49:11.380 --> 00:49:14.560
of our country and
the changes in status,

00:49:14.560 --> 00:49:16.977
if not economic well-being
that that entails.

00:49:16.977 --> 00:49:19.060
This side of it that we
didn't say anything about,

00:49:19.060 --> 00:49:20.601
which I've gotten
more interested in,

00:49:20.601 --> 00:49:25.240
is we basically like
government, right?

00:49:25.240 --> 00:49:28.840
We see it as distorted
in many ways.

00:49:28.840 --> 00:49:32.230
And the irony is that we think
that there's-- on the right,

00:49:32.230 --> 00:49:35.890
people talk, I think correctly,
about crony capitalism.

00:49:35.890 --> 00:49:39.714
And then they say the cure
is to essentially cut back,

00:49:39.714 --> 00:49:40.630
eliminate, government.

00:49:40.630 --> 00:49:43.150
It's like a form
of bloodletting.

00:49:43.150 --> 00:49:45.040
If we crippled
government, then it

00:49:45.040 --> 00:49:46.465
can't be used for
these purposes.

00:49:51.910 --> 00:49:54.790
And so we're basically saying,
let's take back government

00:49:54.790 --> 00:49:58.240
for the positive purpose
that our founders understood,

00:49:58.240 --> 00:50:01.090
Adam Smith understood, and the
leaders of the 20th century

00:50:01.090 --> 00:50:01.860
understood.

00:50:01.860 --> 00:50:06.400
But there was a predatory
state, and its orientation

00:50:06.400 --> 00:50:09.160
towards African-Americans
in particular

00:50:09.160 --> 00:50:12.340
does not look this
benevolent at all.

00:50:12.340 --> 00:50:15.670
Look at the Ferguson report
to see that in action.

00:50:15.670 --> 00:50:19.770
And I think that we, Paul
and I, in writing this book,

00:50:19.770 --> 00:50:21.790
really just did
ourselves a disservice

00:50:21.790 --> 00:50:23.422
by not thinking
more about how this

00:50:23.422 --> 00:50:24.630
fits into the larger picture.

00:50:24.630 --> 00:50:27.420
After all, this decline
in trust in government

00:50:27.420 --> 00:50:30.400
and in the presence of the
state in a positive way

00:50:30.400 --> 00:50:32.350
in our economy
occurs simultaneously

00:50:32.350 --> 00:50:34.900
with the rise of
mass incarceration

00:50:34.900 --> 00:50:38.050
and the rise of these very
punitive and extractive

00:50:38.050 --> 00:50:40.350
practices that were revealed
in the Ferguson report.

00:50:40.350 --> 00:50:43.254
So I plead guilty that we
didn't do more on that,

00:50:43.254 --> 00:50:45.170
and I'd love to get your
thoughts about how it

00:50:45.170 --> 00:50:46.900
could be better incorporated.

00:50:46.900 --> 00:50:48.540
Next question.

00:50:48.540 --> 00:50:53.730
- Hi, I'm Jane Mansbridge, and
I teach at the Kennedy School.

00:50:53.730 --> 00:50:57.070
I completely buy your
positive-sum story.

00:50:57.070 --> 00:50:59.670
Toward the end, you said
that a mixed economy

00:50:59.670 --> 00:51:04.030
depends on the ability to
make bipartisan compromises.

00:51:04.030 --> 00:51:04.690
- Yes.

00:51:04.690 --> 00:51:08.920
- And I'm wondering
what to do then?

00:51:08.920 --> 00:51:12.607
Because there are
a large numbers--

00:51:12.607 --> 00:51:13.940
- It depends on unicorns, right?

00:51:13.940 --> 00:51:17.560
- --three major structural
reasons why we're not going

00:51:17.560 --> 00:51:19.210
to get that.

00:51:19.210 --> 00:51:23.070
First of all, Johnson signed the
Civil Rights Act back in 1964.

00:51:23.070 --> 00:51:26.580
The Southern Conservatives
left the Democratic Party.

00:51:26.580 --> 00:51:29.560
Now, you've got two much
more homogeneous parties,

00:51:29.560 --> 00:51:32.820
and they are acting like
homogeneous conflicting

00:51:32.820 --> 00:51:33.320
parties.

00:51:33.320 --> 00:51:34.361
They're not making deals.

00:51:34.361 --> 00:51:37.170
You can't find someone
across the aisle who

00:51:37.170 --> 00:51:39.460
thinks the way you do anymore.

00:51:39.460 --> 00:51:42.250
And then two, as you
know, Nolan McCarty

00:51:42.250 --> 00:51:45.340
has got this
wonderful graph that

00:51:45.340 --> 00:51:48.400
shows-- you all
know that inequality

00:51:48.400 --> 00:51:49.920
has got this great U-curve.

00:51:49.920 --> 00:51:53.100
It turns out that
polarization has got a U-curve

00:51:53.100 --> 00:51:55.800
that maps absolutely onto it.

00:51:55.800 --> 00:51:58.600
So there's a suggestion
that inequality--

00:51:58.600 --> 00:52:00.490
now he's gotten more
detailed, and he

00:52:00.490 --> 00:52:04.480
can begin to show that
inequality causes polarization

00:52:04.480 --> 00:52:06.270
to some degree.

00:52:06.270 --> 00:52:09.652
Well, I don't see inequality
turning around tomorrow.

00:52:09.652 --> 00:52:11.110
That means that
polarization is not

00:52:11.110 --> 00:52:13.620
going to turn around either.

00:52:13.620 --> 00:52:15.960
And then Frances Lee
has got this point,

00:52:15.960 --> 00:52:19.810
which he says that as elections
become more competitive,

00:52:19.810 --> 00:52:24.330
there's no reason for the party
that's the minority to go along

00:52:24.330 --> 00:52:25.750
the way they did
back in the days

00:52:25.750 --> 00:52:28.690
that we consider the
wonderful bipartisan days.

00:52:28.690 --> 00:52:32.710
They were really days
of Democratic dominance.

00:52:32.710 --> 00:52:34.710
And so if you were
Republican, it kind of

00:52:34.710 --> 00:52:37.960
payed you to not
be too obstreperous

00:52:37.960 --> 00:52:40.370
because you weren't going to
get your roads and bridges.

00:52:40.370 --> 00:52:42.630
But as soon as you
think you've got

00:52:42.630 --> 00:52:44.170
the eye on the
next election, you

00:52:44.170 --> 00:52:46.590
think you can actually make
it in the next election,

00:52:46.590 --> 00:52:49.750
then it's in your interest
to keep the party in power

00:52:49.750 --> 00:52:51.250
from doing anything.

00:52:51.250 --> 00:52:53.400
Because then they're
run on their successes,

00:52:53.400 --> 00:52:56.340
if you can keep them from
doing anything, just the way

00:52:56.340 --> 00:52:57.690
you can then say, look--

00:52:57.690 --> 00:52:58.370
- OK.

00:52:58.370 --> 00:52:59.560
I got it, Jane.

00:52:59.560 --> 00:53:00.751
It's really bad.

00:53:00.751 --> 00:53:01.750
- So now, what do we do?

00:53:01.750 --> 00:53:03.990
That's my question.

00:53:03.990 --> 00:53:05.740
- So the first thing
to say is absolutely.

00:53:05.740 --> 00:53:10.440
And one wonders if
bipartisan is the wrong word

00:53:10.440 --> 00:53:13.900
to use in this context,
given, as you say,

00:53:13.900 --> 00:53:18.600
the degree to which
the parties have become

00:53:18.600 --> 00:53:21.000
more homogeneous and distinct.

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:23.460
it may well be that
what I am talking about,

00:53:23.460 --> 00:53:25.960
the kind of compromise, if you
will, that I'm talking about,

00:53:25.960 --> 00:53:30.040
is much more about creating
effective majorities that

00:53:30.040 --> 00:53:33.960
are representing broad middle
of the American electorate.

00:53:33.960 --> 00:53:35.400
And that's not what we've had.

00:53:35.400 --> 00:53:37.899
The way to understand-- and
this is not an original thought.

00:53:37.899 --> 00:53:40.500
This is contained in the work
of Thom Mann and Norm Ornstein

00:53:40.500 --> 00:53:42.810
and Theda's work and
others-- is that we basically

00:53:42.810 --> 00:53:45.870
are developing more unified
parties, although not unified

00:53:45.870 --> 00:53:47.482
always in the way
that we typically

00:53:47.482 --> 00:53:48.440
would think of parties.

00:53:48.440 --> 00:53:50.980
The Republican
Party both has had

00:53:50.980 --> 00:53:53.620
in recent years has both been
highly unified in its voting

00:53:53.620 --> 00:53:55.290
patterns and highly
fractious as well,

00:53:55.290 --> 00:53:57.210
in terms of its
leadership choices.

00:53:57.210 --> 00:54:03.090
But we have unified parties of
a almost parliamentary style

00:54:03.090 --> 00:54:05.290
in a separation of power system.

00:54:05.290 --> 00:54:07.830
And if you go back to
the writing of Juan Linz

00:54:07.830 --> 00:54:09.544
and other theorists
of parliamentary

00:54:09.544 --> 00:54:10.960
versus presidential
system, that's

00:54:10.960 --> 00:54:12.670
a really bad combination, right?

00:54:12.670 --> 00:54:14.440
It leads to instability.

00:54:14.440 --> 00:54:17.020
It leads to the potential
for a sort of authoritarian

00:54:17.020 --> 00:54:20.560
to come to power, promising he
can break through the gridlock.

00:54:20.560 --> 00:54:23.040
I would never think
that could happen.

00:54:23.040 --> 00:54:28.560
And it also is very hard to
hold parties accountable,

00:54:28.560 --> 00:54:32.310
which is after all the
ideal of party government,

00:54:32.310 --> 00:54:34.956
was that one party is
in power, and based

00:54:34.956 --> 00:54:37.080
on the performance of the
economy and other things,

00:54:37.080 --> 00:54:38.913
you can decide whether
you should keep them.

00:54:38.913 --> 00:54:40.980
Are you better off than
you were four years ago?

00:54:40.980 --> 00:54:42.850
In our system,
who's in charge when

00:54:42.850 --> 00:54:46.442
the presidency is held by
one party and Congress,

00:54:46.442 --> 00:54:48.400
or one branch of Congress
is held by the other?

00:54:48.400 --> 00:54:50.520
That is, as I say,
part of the reason why

00:54:50.520 --> 00:54:53.350
the backlash against Republicans
could be quite consequential,

00:54:53.350 --> 00:54:56.160
because there is a much
more unified accountability

00:54:56.160 --> 00:54:57.540
than there has been recently.

00:54:57.540 --> 00:55:02.070
So what does it require
to create more pressure

00:55:02.070 --> 00:55:06.440
for moderate outcomes,
which might be--

00:55:06.440 --> 00:55:09.540
and in irony, I think our book
is basically saying we need

00:55:09.540 --> 00:55:11.660
radical change to create
moderate outcomes,

00:55:11.660 --> 00:55:14.201
which I know is not a rallying
cry that many people are going

00:55:14.201 --> 00:55:15.080
to get behind.

00:55:15.080 --> 00:55:17.300
Well, I think the big
thing we shouldn't forget

00:55:17.300 --> 00:55:20.690
is that, first of all,
pressure from the edges,

00:55:20.690 --> 00:55:24.800
and particularly in the US,
given the weakness of the left

00:55:24.800 --> 00:55:29.450
relative to the organized right,
is an important part of pulling

00:55:29.450 --> 00:55:31.250
people to the center.

00:55:31.250 --> 00:55:35.160
A second thing I would
mention that I think

00:55:35.160 --> 00:55:39.140
is very important and
somewhat neglected,

00:55:39.140 --> 00:55:42.290
is that I've never seen a
case in American history

00:55:42.290 --> 00:55:44.582
where elites just sort of
decide they're going to-- out

00:55:44.582 --> 00:55:46.414
of the goodness of their
heart, that they're

00:55:46.414 --> 00:55:49.250
going to come to some kind of
compromise that's positive-sum.

00:55:49.250 --> 00:55:51.140
It always happens
because of constraint.

00:55:51.140 --> 00:55:53.480
The mid-century business
elite wasn't just

00:55:53.480 --> 00:55:57.170
the greatest generation
of business leaders.

00:55:57.170 --> 00:55:58.700
They had to face
organized labor.

00:55:58.700 --> 00:56:00.540
They had to deal with
moderate Republicans.

00:56:00.540 --> 00:56:02.120
So how do you create constraint?

00:56:02.120 --> 00:56:04.703
If it's not going to come from
labor, where does it come from?

00:56:04.703 --> 00:56:06.200
What kind of organizations?

00:56:06.200 --> 00:56:08.810
As a very important
starting point,

00:56:08.810 --> 00:56:10.496
you can't expect
it just-- you could

00:56:10.496 --> 00:56:12.620
have a strategy for winning
elections that involves

00:56:12.620 --> 00:56:14.300
being in just a few
places in the country

00:56:14.300 --> 00:56:16.200
because you have to
create ongoing constraint

00:56:16.200 --> 00:56:17.000
on governance.

00:56:17.000 --> 00:56:18.950
That means the
Democratic Party has

00:56:18.950 --> 00:56:21.060
to be a 50-state
party, as often said.

00:56:21.060 --> 00:56:24.200
It means the
organization on the left

00:56:24.200 --> 00:56:25.520
can't just be in Washington.

00:56:25.520 --> 00:56:26.040
Right?

00:56:26.040 --> 00:56:27.498
They have to be
federated, as Theda

00:56:27.498 --> 00:56:28.895
has argued in much of her work.

00:56:28.895 --> 00:56:33.342
Lastly, and I think kind of
cuts against the grain of some

00:56:33.342 --> 00:56:34.800
of the political
science consensus,

00:56:34.800 --> 00:56:35.930
but I want to say it.

00:56:35.930 --> 00:56:37.789
I think that our low
levels of turnout,

00:56:37.789 --> 00:56:39.830
and particularly the
disparities between mid-term

00:56:39.830 --> 00:56:42.200
and presidential election
years, is an enormous part

00:56:42.200 --> 00:56:43.370
of the problem here.

00:56:43.370 --> 00:56:46.170
And that to get
more people engaged

00:56:46.170 --> 00:56:48.920
in politics on a sustained
basis, not just voting,

00:56:48.920 --> 00:56:52.040
but as a gateway to other
forms of organization, voting,

00:56:52.040 --> 00:56:53.630
and especially in
midterm years, would

00:56:53.630 --> 00:56:55.670
make a tremendous difference.

00:56:55.670 --> 00:56:57.500
And it would make a
difference in part

00:56:57.500 --> 00:57:00.130
because it would create
much greater chance

00:57:00.130 --> 00:57:02.900
of the kind of accountability
that I was talking about,

00:57:02.900 --> 00:57:05.632
not the-- essentially,
you get two years,

00:57:05.632 --> 00:57:07.590
and then the other party
is going to crush you.

00:57:07.590 --> 00:57:09.200
And let's just be clear.

00:57:09.200 --> 00:57:11.060
There's an asymmetry
between the parties

00:57:11.060 --> 00:57:13.230
in how this system works
because the Republican

00:57:13.230 --> 00:57:16.340
Party has become the party of
low turnout election years.

00:57:16.340 --> 00:57:19.116
It's become the party
of older, whiter voters.

00:57:19.116 --> 00:57:21.240
That didn't used to be the
case-- and rural voters.

00:57:21.240 --> 00:57:22.770
That didn't used to be the case.

00:57:22.770 --> 00:57:25.700
Now, a democratic
presidency and Congress

00:57:25.700 --> 00:57:28.772
has two years before
midterm wipes it out.

00:57:28.772 --> 00:57:30.230
And with the
Republican party, they

00:57:30.230 --> 00:57:32.599
don't have that same conflict.

00:57:32.599 --> 00:57:34.640
And the only way we're
going to create a conflict

00:57:34.640 --> 00:57:38.170
is if there's high
turnout on both sides

00:57:38.170 --> 00:57:39.860
in non-president election years.

00:57:39.860 --> 00:57:41.830
Next question.

00:57:41.830 --> 00:57:44.900
- June Sekera with the Global
Development and Environment

00:57:44.900 --> 00:57:47.960
Institute at Tufts, and
where we have recently

00:57:47.960 --> 00:57:52.230
launched a project on
the public economy.

00:57:52.230 --> 00:57:53.570
- Wonderful.

00:57:53.570 --> 00:57:57.980
- Something that doesn't
exist in economics.

00:57:57.980 --> 00:58:04.130
And I actually spent 25 years
of my life or more in government

00:58:04.130 --> 00:58:06.840
at the federal, state, and
local levels in management

00:58:06.840 --> 00:58:08.370
and leadership positions.

00:58:08.370 --> 00:58:13.580
And I watched, basically, the
marketization of government

00:58:13.580 --> 00:58:14.450
at all three levels.

00:58:14.450 --> 00:58:18.840
It happened-- all three
levels as I worked at them.

00:58:18.840 --> 00:58:21.510
And what we have is a government
that's been taken over

00:58:21.510 --> 00:58:26.120
by the economic market model.

00:58:26.120 --> 00:58:31.340
And the religion, the
ideology of market economics

00:58:31.340 --> 00:58:34.640
is basically
permeated government

00:58:34.640 --> 00:58:43.230
and is the rationale by which
much of government is run.

00:58:43.230 --> 00:58:45.750
I read your book,
and I really want

00:58:45.750 --> 00:58:47.750
to say that I am very
appreciative that you talk

00:58:47.750 --> 00:58:51.860
about how redistribution--
how so many think

00:58:51.860 --> 00:58:54.480
of government as just-- a
major role is redistribution.

00:58:54.480 --> 00:58:56.500
It does very much more.

00:58:56.500 --> 00:59:00.320
But my question is, you talk
about the mixed economy.

00:59:00.320 --> 00:59:05.450
And that term, which
many people use,

00:59:05.450 --> 00:59:06.950
sort of leaves the
question hanging.

00:59:06.950 --> 00:59:10.310
A mix of market and what?

00:59:10.310 --> 00:59:14.960
And so what I have been
working on, and others,

00:59:14.960 --> 00:59:18.950
and it's in my recent in my
recent book on The Public

00:59:18.950 --> 00:59:24.480
Economy in Crisis, is that
there are multiple economies.

00:59:24.480 --> 00:59:26.630
There's the market
economy, and there is

00:59:26.630 --> 00:59:29.810
the public non-market economy.

00:59:29.810 --> 00:59:32.830
And we need a theory of the
public non-market economy,

00:59:32.830 --> 00:59:34.500
which we are working on.

00:59:34.500 --> 00:59:35.000
- Great.

00:59:35.000 --> 00:59:36.458
- But I wondered
if you had thought

00:59:36.458 --> 00:59:39.080
about that, the term
mixed economy, and also

00:59:39.080 --> 00:59:43.310
the question of the
thumb versus the fingers?

00:59:43.310 --> 00:59:45.560
The government is actually--
the public economy

00:59:45.560 --> 00:59:46.870
is actually a producer.

00:59:46.870 --> 00:59:49.910
Paul Studenski wrote
about this in the 1920s

00:59:49.910 --> 00:59:52.546
very eloquently as
government as a producer.

00:59:52.546 --> 00:59:54.420
So I wonder if you had
talked about that, you

00:59:54.420 --> 00:59:55.878
and your co-author,
and whether you

00:59:55.878 --> 00:59:59.450
had any thoughts about the
mixed economy versus there

00:59:59.450 --> 01:00:01.027
being a public economy?

01:00:01.027 --> 01:00:01.860
- Thank you so much.

01:00:01.860 --> 01:00:04.270
Yeah, and I'm so glad that
this project is taking place.

01:00:04.270 --> 01:00:08.150
And I do think that--
as a very first gloss

01:00:08.150 --> 01:00:10.620
on what you were saying,
I think we definitely

01:00:10.620 --> 01:00:13.940
are not suggesting that a
mixed economy simply consists

01:00:13.940 --> 01:00:15.880
of marketing government.

01:00:15.880 --> 01:00:16.380
Right?

01:00:16.380 --> 01:00:21.484
There's a huge nonprofit
voluntary sector as well.

01:00:21.484 --> 01:00:23.150
And we shouldn't
forget the way in which

01:00:23.150 --> 01:00:27.870
the economy rests on the
quantity of households as well.

01:00:27.870 --> 01:00:30.000
So I agree with that.

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:34.880
I think that this is the
best metaphor I've heard,

01:00:34.880 --> 01:00:37.339
but it does have this
problem that it suggests

01:00:37.339 --> 01:00:38.880
that the role of
government is mostly

01:00:38.880 --> 01:00:40.784
kind of pushing
back and regulatory,

01:00:40.784 --> 01:00:42.450
and that's not at all
what we're saying.

01:00:42.450 --> 01:00:43.650
A lot of what I
was talking about

01:00:43.650 --> 01:00:45.860
was kind of the fuel for
the engine of prosperity.

01:00:45.860 --> 01:00:47.610
And in fact, the
big problem I see

01:00:47.610 --> 01:00:51.000
is that we're not actually
replenishing that tank.

01:00:51.000 --> 01:00:53.570
And so we're going to be
running on fumes more and more.

01:00:53.570 --> 01:00:56.820
If we look at the digital
economy and the breakthroughs

01:00:56.820 --> 01:01:00.150
that resulted, there were
1950s and '60s investments.

01:01:00.150 --> 01:01:02.760
And where are we making
those investments today?

01:01:02.760 --> 01:01:06.110
In some areas, but far too
little and far too late.

01:01:06.110 --> 01:01:11.630
So what I didn't say
about the productive side

01:01:11.630 --> 01:01:13.840
in marketization is-- and
if we could just pull up

01:01:13.840 --> 01:01:16.860
this slide that I put up here.

01:01:16.860 --> 01:01:21.060
So this is the chart that--
I just found it today--

01:01:21.060 --> 01:01:22.944
that sort of shows
why everything we

01:01:22.944 --> 01:01:25.110
think we know about the
federal government is wrong.

01:01:25.110 --> 01:01:26.400
So the federal
government is spending

01:01:26.400 --> 01:01:27.524
a lot more than it used to.

01:01:27.524 --> 01:01:29.250
But in terms of
civilian employment,

01:01:29.250 --> 01:01:32.610
it's basically been
relying increasingly

01:01:32.610 --> 01:01:37.460
on third-party contractors
and privatization.

01:01:37.460 --> 01:01:39.574
So this is total
civilian employment

01:01:39.574 --> 01:01:40.740
as a share of the workforce.

01:01:40.740 --> 01:01:43.250
And I think we point out in
the book that to get back

01:01:43.250 --> 01:01:47.355
to the Eisenhower-level era
levels-- in John [INAUDIBLE]

01:01:47.355 --> 01:01:48.980
has pointed this
out-- you have to hire

01:01:48.980 --> 01:01:52.020
like two million federal
workers tomorrow.

01:01:52.020 --> 01:01:54.254
And right now, Donald
Trump is proposing a freeze

01:01:54.254 --> 01:01:55.670
on federal hiring,
which continues

01:01:55.670 --> 01:01:57.960
a kind of Republican call.

01:01:57.960 --> 01:01:59.520
And what happens in the absence?

01:01:59.520 --> 01:02:01.710
And we can see this too
in congressional committee

01:02:01.710 --> 01:02:04.800
staff, which as our society
grew much more complex,

01:02:04.800 --> 01:02:07.214
and Congress's role in
legislating increased,

01:02:07.214 --> 01:02:09.380
there was this enormous
increase in committee staff.

01:02:09.380 --> 01:02:11.630
This come from the
work of Lee Drutman.

01:02:11.630 --> 01:02:14.960
And in recent
decades, of course,

01:02:14.960 --> 01:02:18.326
really centering around
the rise of Newt Gingrich

01:02:18.326 --> 01:02:19.950
and the Republican
capture of Congress,

01:02:19.950 --> 01:02:21.630
there's been a dramatic decline.

01:02:21.630 --> 01:02:24.000
And the result is at the
same time, of course,

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:26.300
there's just been
enormous outside spending.

01:02:26.300 --> 01:02:31.560
This is a world in which
the one side has essentially

01:02:31.560 --> 01:02:34.190
weaponized, and the
other side is disarmed.

01:02:34.190 --> 01:02:37.940
And not having an effective
public sector in that context

01:02:37.940 --> 01:02:40.020
leads to precisely
these kind of dynamics.

01:02:40.020 --> 01:02:45.920
I think this, to me, is probably
the most likely evolution

01:02:45.920 --> 01:02:48.270
of the American mixed
economy under Donald Trump.

01:02:48.270 --> 01:02:51.090
There's going to be this
kind of cut back right

01:02:51.090 --> 01:02:54.090
conservative move that will
be centered around Ryan.

01:02:54.090 --> 01:02:56.630
But to the extent that Trump
himself is putting his imprint

01:02:56.630 --> 01:02:59.400
on an economic
policy, I think it's

01:02:59.400 --> 01:03:02.820
going to be much more around
these kinds of opportunities

01:03:02.820 --> 01:03:07.090
for private profit
through public power.

01:03:07.090 --> 01:03:09.790
And some of it will
be his own profit.

01:03:09.790 --> 01:03:13.530
And there is times when
that actually can work.

01:03:13.530 --> 01:03:15.630
If you think about
the post-war era

01:03:15.630 --> 01:03:19.200
and what's sometimes called the
military complex, but really

01:03:19.200 --> 01:03:22.620
was the military industrial
academic complex-- when

01:03:22.620 --> 01:03:28.380
you use decentralized means and
competition to, for example,

01:03:28.380 --> 01:03:32.580
design weapons systems or
to come up with new research

01:03:32.580 --> 01:03:34.700
and development ideas
or do basic science,

01:03:34.700 --> 01:03:36.810
it can work it can
work extremely well.

01:03:36.810 --> 01:03:39.210
But it's, note,
not an area where

01:03:39.210 --> 01:03:43.400
the profit motive is really the
fundamental source of pressure.

01:03:43.400 --> 01:03:45.650
And what we see in this
private predation--

01:03:45.650 --> 01:03:47.820
I mean state predation
I was talking about,

01:03:47.820 --> 01:03:49.466
is like what's
happened in Ferguson.

01:03:49.466 --> 01:03:51.090
It was all about
creating opportunities

01:03:51.090 --> 01:03:52.590
for the private
sector, essentially,

01:03:52.590 --> 01:03:56.670
to extract from citizens
who became essentially

01:03:56.670 --> 01:04:01.170
indebted to for-profit
industries that

01:04:01.170 --> 01:04:03.441
preyed on them, thanks
to the opportunities

01:04:03.441 --> 01:04:04.440
that government created.

01:04:04.440 --> 01:04:05.910
And government was
collecting a few pennies

01:04:05.910 --> 01:04:07.620
on the dollar of this
private predation.

01:04:07.620 --> 01:04:11.310
So there is a way
in which we have

01:04:11.310 --> 01:04:14.550
to keep this metaphor in mind
because the thumb isn't just

01:04:14.550 --> 01:04:16.500
about pushing back
in regulatory terms

01:04:16.500 --> 01:04:18.430
or pushing for investment.

01:04:18.430 --> 01:04:21.060
It's also about disciplining
and holding back

01:04:21.060 --> 01:04:24.840
the power of market actors to
subvert the political process.

01:04:24.840 --> 01:04:26.670
That is the
fundamental dialectic

01:04:26.670 --> 01:04:29.070
of democratic capitalism.

01:04:29.070 --> 01:04:33.990
And to me, if there is one
message that comes out of this,

01:04:33.990 --> 01:04:37.190
is that you need to have a
state that's strong enough

01:04:37.190 --> 01:04:42.380
to resist the inevitable
concentrations

01:04:42.380 --> 01:04:46.380
of economic power that result
in a capitalist economy, which

01:04:46.380 --> 01:04:48.320
is not an
anti-capitalist position.

01:04:48.320 --> 01:04:50.920
It's essential for
making capitalism work.

01:04:50.920 --> 01:04:52.860
Yes, so next question.

01:04:52.860 --> 01:04:54.020
- Hi, my name is Lucas.

01:04:54.020 --> 01:04:56.660
I'm just a citizen
of Massachusetts.

01:04:56.660 --> 01:04:57.470
- Just?

01:04:57.470 --> 01:04:59.090
No.

01:04:59.090 --> 01:04:59.900
That's great.

01:04:59.900 --> 01:05:01.670
- So two things, I guess.

01:05:01.670 --> 01:05:04.560
One is, what's
driving this amnesia?

01:05:04.560 --> 01:05:05.060
Right?

01:05:05.060 --> 01:05:06.740
Is it really just all politics?

01:05:06.740 --> 01:05:11.270
Is it a Republican strategy
to sow distrust in government?

01:05:11.270 --> 01:05:12.020
Is that really it?

01:05:12.020 --> 01:05:16.490
Or maybe the second component
is, what does media play?

01:05:16.490 --> 01:05:18.040
How does the media play a role?

01:05:18.040 --> 01:05:20.930
I'm sure we've all heard
about the fake news epidemic

01:05:20.930 --> 01:05:23.240
and how that's been
sort of creating

01:05:23.240 --> 01:05:25.130
echo chambers, especially
in social media

01:05:25.130 --> 01:05:30.230
among conservatives, just
not factual statements being

01:05:30.230 --> 01:05:32.990
promulgated across the internet
and being taken as truth,

01:05:32.990 --> 01:05:35.090
and how that factors
in in all of this.

01:05:35.090 --> 01:05:35.960
Thank you very much.

01:05:35.960 --> 01:05:36.560
- Thank you.

01:05:36.560 --> 01:05:37.170
Yeah.

01:05:37.170 --> 01:05:39.800
Well, so I want to be clear.

01:05:39.800 --> 01:05:41.780
One of the strange
things about this book

01:05:41.780 --> 01:05:43.460
is that Paul and I have
gotten a lot of pushback

01:05:43.460 --> 01:05:45.418
from people who say that
we're too much focused

01:05:45.418 --> 01:05:48.020
on ideas, which is something
I've never been accused of.

01:05:48.020 --> 01:05:50.150
You just saw this whole
talk about organizations

01:05:50.150 --> 01:05:51.650
and political movements.

01:05:51.650 --> 01:05:55.070
But I do think there is a
cultural shift that we're

01:05:55.070 --> 01:06:01.110
talking about that is reflective
of the lead organization

01:06:01.110 --> 01:06:05.600
in investment and probably
is also reflective of broader

01:06:05.600 --> 01:06:08.289
changes in our society that,
say, Daniel Rodgers writes

01:06:08.289 --> 01:06:09.830
about in his book
The Age of Fracture

01:06:09.830 --> 01:06:11.880
towards a greater
emphasis on individualism.

01:06:11.880 --> 01:06:14.750
But one thing I would
say is that that kind

01:06:14.750 --> 01:06:20.300
of individuation, a sense
of personal empowerment,

01:06:20.300 --> 01:06:23.270
is compatible with a lot of
different and better models

01:06:23.270 --> 01:06:24.260
of capitalism.

01:06:24.260 --> 01:06:26.990
So it gets channeled into
this much, much more kind

01:06:26.990 --> 01:06:31.067
of dog-eat-dog limited
government ideology.

01:06:31.067 --> 01:06:32.900
So I just want to say
a word about the media

01:06:32.900 --> 01:06:34.970
because I think that's a really
interesting and important

01:06:34.970 --> 01:06:35.510
question.

01:06:35.510 --> 01:06:38.390
And in the book, we
talk a lot about the way

01:06:38.390 --> 01:06:43.700
in which Fox News and talk radio
really drove the increasing

01:06:43.700 --> 01:06:45.800
intensification of the
Republican base, which

01:06:45.800 --> 01:06:50.120
in turn, fed into the way in
which the GOP shifted right

01:06:50.120 --> 01:06:50.830
over time.

01:06:50.830 --> 01:06:53.570
And you really can't
overstate the role.

01:06:53.570 --> 01:06:55.940
It's not that Fox News is
convincing a lot of swing

01:06:55.940 --> 01:06:57.710
voters to vote for Republicans.

01:06:57.710 --> 01:06:59.450
There's a little
evidence that when

01:06:59.450 --> 01:07:01.190
it is introduced
into media markets,

01:07:01.190 --> 01:07:03.080
that it pulls
candidates to the right.

01:07:03.080 --> 01:07:06.260
But the real story is the degree
to which it becomes a vehicle,

01:07:06.260 --> 01:07:08.370
and this was true in
the Tea Party's rise.

01:07:08.370 --> 01:07:11.540
A vehicle for
mobilizing and focusing

01:07:11.540 --> 01:07:14.990
the energy of
conservative activists

01:07:14.990 --> 01:07:18.410
and ordinary citizens who are
intense and willing to get out

01:07:18.410 --> 01:07:19.280
there.

01:07:19.280 --> 01:07:22.060
The Tea Party was a
remarkable organization.

01:07:22.060 --> 01:07:25.280
And once again, I drew
a lot on Theda's work

01:07:25.280 --> 01:07:26.450
in thinking about it.

01:07:26.450 --> 01:07:27.920
It's a remarkable
organization that

01:07:27.920 --> 01:07:31.010
involved-- it is a
decentralized, federated

01:07:31.010 --> 01:07:34.700
organization that has
lots of mass input.

01:07:34.700 --> 01:07:37.880
There is something there that we
should understand for building

01:07:37.880 --> 01:07:38.810
broader organizations.

01:07:38.810 --> 01:07:40.352
But one piece of it
that is very hard

01:07:40.352 --> 01:07:42.476
to think about how you
would replicate it elsewhere

01:07:42.476 --> 01:07:45.020
is the way in which Fox News
and conservative talk radio

01:07:45.020 --> 01:07:47.990
plays a kind of amplifying
role in that world.

01:07:47.990 --> 01:07:50.360
The mainstream media,
as we sometimes call it,

01:07:50.360 --> 01:07:53.900
has really not done
us a very good job,

01:07:53.900 --> 01:07:58.290
to put it bluntly--
to put it mildly.

01:07:58.290 --> 01:08:01.800
So the two things that I
think about the media here.

01:08:01.800 --> 01:08:05.300
One is that-- Dan
Rather was once

01:08:05.300 --> 01:08:07.930
asked what the goal of
the nightly news was,

01:08:07.930 --> 01:08:10.270
and he said to survive.

01:08:10.270 --> 01:08:10.770
right?

01:08:10.770 --> 01:08:12.410
They're under enormous
competitive pressure,

01:08:12.410 --> 01:08:13.326
and they're declining.

01:08:13.326 --> 01:08:15.800
Lots of people have tuned out
from the mainstream media.

01:08:15.800 --> 01:08:17.930
And the media is in a tailspin.

01:08:17.930 --> 01:08:19.479
In fact, to the
extent that it's been

01:08:19.479 --> 01:08:21.020
able to hold on in
recent years, it's

01:08:21.020 --> 01:08:24.500
by doing a kind of
conflict-oriented,

01:08:24.500 --> 01:08:28.490
horse-race-oriented,
hyperventilation kind

01:08:28.490 --> 01:08:31.880
of coverage that doesn't
really inform people very much.

01:08:31.880 --> 01:08:36.560
And that is-- I'm not
saying the media was once

01:08:36.560 --> 01:08:37.964
like a civics lesson.

01:08:37.964 --> 01:08:39.380
But the degree to
which people are

01:08:39.380 --> 01:08:44.672
getting important information
about policy or other features

01:08:44.672 --> 01:08:46.880
of public affairs from the
media has really declined.

01:08:46.880 --> 01:08:49.850
The other thing the media does
is reinforce this negative view

01:08:49.850 --> 01:08:50.439
of government.

01:08:50.439 --> 01:08:52.130
And there's a headline
you'll never see.

01:08:52.130 --> 01:08:54.386
It's, "Things are
getting better, slowly,

01:08:54.386 --> 01:08:55.510
because of the government."

01:08:55.510 --> 01:08:56.240
Right?

01:08:56.240 --> 01:08:58.515
It's just like your eyes
are already-- your eyelids

01:08:58.515 --> 01:08:59.390
are already drooping.

01:08:59.390 --> 01:09:01.520
But that's the truth
in a lot of areas.

01:09:01.520 --> 01:09:04.520
We have looked at a lot of
studies of media coverage,

01:09:04.520 --> 01:09:06.229
and the negativity
bias, particularly

01:09:06.229 --> 01:09:09.050
around public policy, is
really an important reason

01:09:09.050 --> 01:09:12.170
why people don't understand
some of the positive benefits

01:09:12.170 --> 01:09:13.010
of public policy.

01:09:13.010 --> 01:09:15.040
So I wouldn't put too
much emphasis on it,

01:09:15.040 --> 01:09:17.540
but I do think, especially in
terms of ginning up the right,

01:09:17.540 --> 01:09:18.706
has been really fundamental.

01:09:18.706 --> 01:09:21.671
Thanks, Lucas.

01:09:21.671 --> 01:09:22.170
- Hi.

01:09:22.170 --> 01:09:23.569
My name is Jonathan [INAUDIBLE].

01:09:23.569 --> 01:09:25.302
I'm also a member of the public.

01:09:25.302 --> 01:09:27.260
First of all, thank you
very much for the talk.

01:09:27.260 --> 01:09:28.460
- Thanks, Jonathan.

01:09:28.460 --> 01:09:30.576
- So you mentioned at
some point in your talk.

01:09:30.576 --> 01:09:31.450
I think it was early.

01:09:31.450 --> 01:09:34.220
You said the institutions
we have are effective.

01:09:34.220 --> 01:09:36.390
But you've obviously
talked about some problems.

01:09:36.390 --> 01:09:38.306
And we see them, like
gerrymandering, Citizens

01:09:38.306 --> 01:09:40.220
United, voter suppression.

01:09:40.220 --> 01:09:41.990
And you also said
Mitch McConnell solved

01:09:41.990 --> 01:09:43.520
the problem of governance.

01:09:43.520 --> 01:09:48.439
So my question is,
are you convinced

01:09:48.439 --> 01:09:50.210
that maybe institutions--
and I'm even

01:09:50.210 --> 01:09:54.300
thinking in particular the
structure of the Constitution,

01:09:54.300 --> 01:09:55.730
not at a really
fundamental level.

01:09:55.730 --> 01:09:57.634
But are there any
amendments that are needed

01:09:57.634 --> 01:10:00.050
or changes that are needed to
address any of these issues?

01:10:00.050 --> 01:10:02.940
Do you think that, as we are
right now, if nothing changes,

01:10:02.940 --> 01:10:05.310
that things will in
fact be able to improve?

01:10:05.310 --> 01:10:06.070
- Well, thanks.

01:10:06.070 --> 01:10:06.570
Yes.

01:10:06.570 --> 01:10:08.660
So I hope that my
message that came across

01:10:08.660 --> 01:10:11.110
wasn't that our current
institutions are effective.

01:10:11.110 --> 01:10:18.170
My point was only that we could
achieve a better mixed economy

01:10:18.170 --> 01:10:21.320
without the kind of fundamental
constitutional reform that

01:10:21.320 --> 01:10:23.990
sometimes gets held
up as the only path

01:10:23.990 --> 01:10:25.760
to economic redemption.

01:10:25.760 --> 01:10:30.440
And in terms of McConnell, the
point I was making is simply

01:10:30.440 --> 01:10:36.350
that McConnell realized that if
the Republican party was able

01:10:36.350 --> 01:10:40.190
to fail to cooperate-- one
way to think about this--

01:10:40.190 --> 01:10:42.620
I'm sorry to step back, but
one way to think about this

01:10:42.620 --> 01:10:48.090
is in a parliamentary
system, and at least

01:10:48.090 --> 01:10:50.930
in your idealized images,
if you're the opposition,

01:10:50.930 --> 01:10:52.010
you're not in government.

01:10:52.010 --> 01:10:52.820
Right?

01:10:52.820 --> 01:10:54.740
But what the Republicans
have been able to do

01:10:54.740 --> 01:10:57.020
is both be the loyal
opposition, thus

01:10:57.020 --> 01:10:59.000
reaping the reward
when governance is bad,

01:10:59.000 --> 01:11:01.610
and also to make governance
nearly impossible.

01:11:01.610 --> 01:11:03.830
That combination is a toxic one.

01:11:03.830 --> 01:11:07.190
And so there are ways in which
we can make that less possible.

01:11:07.190 --> 01:11:09.650
They're not easy, and they
wouldn't necessarily--

01:11:09.650 --> 01:11:12.740
and I don't think they would
probably, from a standpoint,

01:11:12.740 --> 01:11:15.010
should involve
constitutional amendments.

01:11:15.010 --> 01:11:19.130
So for one thing, as
I said, is the degree

01:11:19.130 --> 01:11:21.299
to which you have two
electorates, mid-term

01:11:21.299 --> 01:11:23.090
and presidential election
year electorates.

01:11:23.090 --> 01:11:25.298
Not to mention, that filters
down to the state level.

01:11:25.298 --> 01:11:28.100
Most governors are elected not
in presidential election years.

01:11:28.100 --> 01:11:30.380
Where they are elected in
president election years,

01:11:30.380 --> 01:11:32.600
Democrats are much
more likely to win.

01:11:32.600 --> 01:11:36.140
So it's actually, I think
would be quite helpful to think

01:11:36.140 --> 01:11:38.000
about, OK, well how
do you make midterms

01:11:38.000 --> 01:11:40.560
and how do you make off-year
elections much higher turnout

01:11:40.560 --> 01:11:42.260
affairs?

01:11:42.260 --> 01:11:43.970
The other thing,
as I said, is a lot

01:11:43.970 --> 01:11:46.100
of this is about outside
organization and creation

01:11:46.100 --> 01:11:50.720
of constraint so that our
political system once-- it's

01:11:50.720 --> 01:11:54.590
always required, and sometimes
it's facilitated compromise.

01:11:54.590 --> 01:11:56.480
And it's facilitated
compromise when

01:11:56.480 --> 01:11:59.552
there's these sources
of outside constraints,

01:11:59.552 --> 01:12:01.010
as well as
cross-cutting cleavages.

01:12:01.010 --> 01:12:03.980
And so trying to create
that outside organizational

01:12:03.980 --> 01:12:05.610
constraint is important as well.

01:12:05.610 --> 01:12:06.770
One thing that I think
would really help,

01:12:06.770 --> 01:12:08.561
and I just don't know
exactly how to do it,

01:12:08.561 --> 01:12:11.030
is you've got to be able to
have some kind of mechanisms

01:12:11.030 --> 01:12:14.590
and some kind of fora for
calling out extremism.

01:12:14.590 --> 01:12:17.510
And let me just-- think
of that if-- would

01:12:17.510 --> 01:12:21.180
this election have
been different if--

01:12:21.180 --> 01:12:23.690
and because obviously,
the media said again

01:12:23.690 --> 01:12:26.000
and again, they're like this
is a reprehensible thing

01:12:26.000 --> 01:12:27.722
that Donald Trump
has said or done.

01:12:27.722 --> 01:12:29.930
But would it have been
different if, instead of that,

01:12:29.930 --> 01:12:32.660
they had kept saying Donald
Trump is actually at odds

01:12:32.660 --> 01:12:34.520
with the Republican party.

01:12:34.520 --> 01:12:35.450
Now, he's not, right?

01:12:35.450 --> 01:12:38.210
Because he owns the
Republican Party, in a sense.

01:12:38.210 --> 01:12:38.840
He helped them.

01:12:38.840 --> 01:12:40.760
And of course, he doesn't
own them in the sense

01:12:40.760 --> 01:12:42.440
that he's setting their
agenda-- Paul Ryan knows what

01:12:42.440 --> 01:12:45.110
he wants to do-- but in a
sense that nothing succeeds

01:12:45.110 --> 01:12:46.320
like success.

01:12:46.320 --> 01:12:49.160
And they're much more likely to
be allied with him as a result.

01:12:49.160 --> 01:12:52.310
But before the election, they
were playing a very, very

01:12:52.310 --> 01:12:54.830
delicate double game.

01:12:54.830 --> 01:12:57.660
And it was, I think,
greatly under-reported.

01:12:57.660 --> 01:12:59.627
And especially among
Republican voters,

01:12:59.627 --> 01:13:01.710
knowing the extent to which
there was this divorce

01:13:01.710 --> 01:13:02.793
would have been important.

01:13:02.793 --> 01:13:04.850
And I think more generally,
the accountability

01:13:04.850 --> 01:13:07.160
can't happen unless people
have some basic idea

01:13:07.160 --> 01:13:09.890
of what's happening
and who's responsible.

01:13:09.890 --> 01:13:13.965
So I think that that creating
that is a difficult challenge,

01:13:13.965 --> 01:13:16.340
but it's one that doesn't
require constitutional changes.

01:13:16.340 --> 01:13:20.270
If I had a couple
Constitutional amendments,

01:13:20.270 --> 01:13:23.990
I would be-- I think
the electoral college is

01:13:23.990 --> 01:13:25.502
an anachronism.

01:13:25.502 --> 01:13:27.710
I'm not a big fan of the
Senate, but that's basically

01:13:27.710 --> 01:13:29.930
beyond amendment.

01:13:29.930 --> 01:13:32.120
So we can talk
about these things.

01:13:32.120 --> 01:13:34.880
But I actually
think that-- and it

01:13:34.880 --> 01:13:38.664
would be nice to have PR in
some parts of the country,

01:13:38.664 --> 01:13:39.830
proportional representation.

01:13:39.830 --> 01:13:43.640
But really, the truth is
that in a lot of respects,

01:13:43.640 --> 01:13:45.320
these are extra
institutional features.

01:13:45.320 --> 01:13:46.986
And even if you believe
the institutions

01:13:46.986 --> 01:13:48.560
can be changed
fundamentally, which

01:13:48.560 --> 01:13:50.910
I don't, that you could
address these problems

01:13:50.910 --> 01:13:51.824
without doing so.

01:13:57.810 --> 01:14:01.320
- Jonathan Martin, sociologist
from Framingham State

01:14:01.320 --> 01:14:01.920
University.

01:14:01.920 --> 01:14:05.355
I'm also a contributing editor
of the recent book Empowering

01:14:05.355 --> 01:14:06.980
Progressive Third
Parties in the United

01:14:06.980 --> 01:14:10.890
States, which was related to
the question I'm going to ask.

01:14:10.890 --> 01:14:13.650
So having read your book
Winner-Take-All Politics,

01:14:13.650 --> 01:14:16.530
I gather that you
don't think the impetus

01:14:16.530 --> 01:14:18.210
for the kind of
change you advocate

01:14:18.210 --> 01:14:19.550
is going to come from elites.

01:14:19.550 --> 01:14:23.040
You talk about the need for
some kind of mass pressure

01:14:23.040 --> 01:14:25.815
to create a more active role
for government in the economy.

01:14:25.815 --> 01:14:28.440
So where do you think the source
of that is going to come from?

01:14:28.440 --> 01:14:31.350
That to me seems like
the huge question here.

01:14:31.350 --> 01:14:33.060
From unions?

01:14:33.060 --> 01:14:34.050
They're small.

01:14:34.050 --> 01:14:38.702
They're representing a declining
segment of the population.

01:14:38.702 --> 01:14:40.910
They're attached to a
democratic establishment that's

01:14:40.910 --> 01:14:43.120
invested in the status quo.

01:14:43.120 --> 01:14:44.620
Some kind of new
social movement?

01:14:44.620 --> 01:14:47.680
Maybe a new Occupy Movement.

01:14:47.680 --> 01:14:49.040
We saw how that fizzled out.

01:14:49.040 --> 01:14:50.000
It had some effect.

01:14:50.000 --> 01:14:51.330
But in the end, it was crushed.

01:14:51.330 --> 01:14:53.085
Is that going to inspire us?

01:14:53.085 --> 01:14:56.970
A Sanders-led uprising?

01:14:56.970 --> 01:14:59.490
Yet, he's up against the
democratic establishment, which

01:14:59.490 --> 01:15:03.370
is sitting on a mountain of
cash and is invested in keeping

01:15:03.370 --> 01:15:04.390
things the way they are.

01:15:04.390 --> 01:15:08.800
Or maybe some kind of a
third-party force arising?

01:15:08.800 --> 01:15:11.550
Third parties did have
some kind of an influence

01:15:11.550 --> 01:15:15.130
in pushing through
critical democratic reforms

01:15:15.130 --> 01:15:18.600
in the 1800s and early 1900s.

01:15:18.600 --> 01:15:20.850
Do you foresee something
like that coming about again?

01:15:20.850 --> 01:15:23.700
Where do you see the force,
this mass pressure coming from

01:15:23.700 --> 01:15:26.260
to create the kind of
change you're proposing?

01:15:26.260 --> 01:15:28.190
- Yeah, well, that
is the big question.

01:15:28.190 --> 01:15:31.770
And let me just say, if
we left the impression

01:15:31.770 --> 01:15:34.210
in Winner-Take-All Politics
that we don't think elites

01:15:34.210 --> 01:15:37.330
are a really important
part of the solution

01:15:37.330 --> 01:15:39.850
as well as the challenge,
then I wasn't clear enough.

01:15:39.850 --> 01:15:43.210
So it's a combination
of elites that

01:15:43.210 --> 01:15:47.920
are constrained by outside
organization and mass pressure

01:15:47.920 --> 01:15:51.080
and elite reformers that really
makes these changes happen.

01:15:51.080 --> 01:15:56.920
And so I would say that
the first order of business

01:15:56.920 --> 01:15:59.200
would be a serious
internal challenge

01:15:59.200 --> 01:16:00.400
within the Democratic Party.

01:16:00.400 --> 01:16:03.420
But not so much on
ideological grounds,

01:16:03.420 --> 01:16:05.980
though as we point
out in the book,

01:16:05.980 --> 01:16:09.100
that the Democratic Party became
deeply cross-pressured because

01:16:09.100 --> 01:16:13.131
of its increased reliance
on money from the business

01:16:13.131 --> 01:16:13.630
community.

01:16:13.630 --> 01:16:18.900
But I actually think right now,
it's an organisationally inept

01:16:18.900 --> 01:16:19.900
party.

01:16:19.900 --> 01:16:21.390
It needs to get
its act together.

01:16:21.390 --> 01:16:23.980
And so I'm not so
much concerned about

01:16:23.980 --> 01:16:28.240
whether people are to the left
of the party or the center--

01:16:28.240 --> 01:16:31.330
and I do think the party
does need to stake out a more

01:16:31.330 --> 01:16:34.090
progressive vision and economic
policy-- but whether or not

01:16:34.090 --> 01:16:36.880
they can actually do things and
build the kind of party that

01:16:36.880 --> 01:16:44.420
can compete nationally
and make their opponents

01:16:44.420 --> 01:16:46.360
have to work for every
victory in a way that

01:16:46.360 --> 01:16:51.580
makes them extremely vulnerable
in future electoral contests.

01:16:51.580 --> 01:16:56.850
So that would be the
immediate vision.

01:16:56.850 --> 01:16:59.140
On the longer-term vision,
you're absolutely right.

01:16:59.140 --> 01:17:03.850
I don't think, and I
wish I could think,

01:17:03.850 --> 01:17:07.780
but I don't think that the
traditional American union

01:17:07.780 --> 01:17:10.270
as we understood it for
most of the 20th century

01:17:10.270 --> 01:17:13.840
has a long future.

01:17:13.840 --> 01:17:16.330
I think it will
continue to have control

01:17:16.330 --> 01:17:17.440
in pockets of the economy.

01:17:17.440 --> 01:17:22.890
But there is no way, I think, to
rebuild a broad working class,

01:17:22.890 --> 01:17:25.242
a middle class
coalition, without having

01:17:25.242 --> 01:17:26.950
some kind of organization
that represents

01:17:26.950 --> 01:17:29.590
the economic interests
of ordinary workers.

01:17:29.590 --> 01:17:32.920
And if it's not going to be
traditional labor unions, what

01:17:32.920 --> 01:17:33.741
is it going to be?

01:17:33.741 --> 01:17:35.740
I really don't know the
answer to that question.

01:17:35.740 --> 01:17:40.020
I have seen some of the sources
in The Fight for Fifteen,

01:17:40.020 --> 01:17:42.480
in the ways in which
it has involved

01:17:42.480 --> 01:17:45.010
cross-racial alliances.

01:17:45.010 --> 01:17:48.100
I would mention the Black
Lives Matter movement as well.

01:17:48.100 --> 01:17:50.080
I've seen some of
the potential for it

01:17:50.080 --> 01:17:54.850
in things that fall short
of collective bargaining,

01:17:54.850 --> 01:17:56.545
but forms of worker
representation that

01:17:56.545 --> 01:17:59.600
are consciousness raising
and bringing people together,

01:17:59.600 --> 01:18:01.960
and that use some
digital technologies,

01:18:01.960 --> 01:18:04.270
but are built ultimately
on ground level

01:18:04.270 --> 01:18:05.950
organization and meetings.

01:18:05.950 --> 01:18:15.730
And finally, I would say
that I see this as, in part,

01:18:15.730 --> 01:18:18.310
a question of
whether or not we're

01:18:18.310 --> 01:18:23.710
going to have a political
movement and leadership that

01:18:23.710 --> 01:18:27.520
is able to make this
difficult case that combines

01:18:27.520 --> 01:18:31.810
a critique of the corruption and
extremism of present government

01:18:31.810 --> 01:18:35.020
and a recognition of the
essential role of government

01:18:35.020 --> 01:18:36.880
in achieving our prosperity.

01:18:36.880 --> 01:18:42.520
And if I was someone who
could write slogans or craft

01:18:42.520 --> 01:18:47.310
effective political strategies,
that's what I would try to do.

01:18:47.310 --> 01:18:48.100
I'm not.

01:18:48.100 --> 01:18:52.340
What I can say is that there
is no future for progressivism

01:18:52.340 --> 01:18:54.880
in the United States
that isn't also

01:18:54.880 --> 01:18:57.790
able and willing to embrace
the active use of government

01:18:57.790 --> 01:18:58.870
in the 21st century.

01:18:58.870 --> 01:19:02.100
And so we're kind of at a
Hamilton moment, if you will.

01:19:02.100 --> 01:19:04.426
And of course, we all
know Alexander Hamilton.

01:19:04.426 --> 01:19:06.880
[LAUGHTER]

01:19:06.880 --> 01:19:09.460
The Articles of
Confederation are--

01:19:09.460 --> 01:19:14.280
we remember the Constitution as
being the Revolution, and then

01:19:14.280 --> 01:19:15.920
the Seinfeld style.

01:19:15.920 --> 01:19:18.760
We go revolution,
yada-yada-yada, Constitution.

01:19:18.760 --> 01:19:19.324
Right?

01:19:19.324 --> 01:19:21.240
But there's a big thing
in the yada-yada-yada.

01:19:21.240 --> 01:19:23.830
That's the Articles of
Confederation, the failure

01:19:23.830 --> 01:19:24.810
of institutional form.

01:19:24.810 --> 01:19:26.987
I believe right now,
if you look at the IRS,

01:19:26.987 --> 01:19:28.570
if you look at
discretionary spending,

01:19:28.570 --> 01:19:32.560
if you look at all of
these crucial areas

01:19:32.560 --> 01:19:34.330
of public authority,
we're moving

01:19:34.330 --> 01:19:37.830
toward the kind of
ineffective public authority

01:19:37.830 --> 01:19:40.460
that that is corrupt
and incapable.

01:19:40.460 --> 01:19:43.590
It's like the perfect
negative combination.

01:19:43.590 --> 01:19:49.480
And that we cannot rebuild
a strong and effective left

01:19:49.480 --> 01:19:53.620
or a strong and effective union
movement without rebuilding

01:19:53.620 --> 01:19:55.920
a strong and effective
government as well.

01:19:55.920 --> 01:19:57.050
So thank you.

01:19:57.050 --> 01:19:59.150
